green line crosses the price from the top-down, that is a sell signal.\n\n== The key elements of Ichimoku's Time Theory ==\n\nGoichi Hosoda also developed the time theory by differentiating 3-time ranges and two different levels: simple and compound.\n\n===Numerical values===\n\nSimple ranges\n[[File:= SIMPLE ranges.png|thumb|Simple ranges at Ichimoku]]\n\nCompound ranges\n[[File:= COMPOUND RANGES.png|thumb|Compound ranges at Ichimoku]]\n\n===Equality in the numerical values or Taitou-Suchi===\n\nHen-Gi: Using a numerical value that happened before and applying it from another\n\nJyu-Gi: Proposing a numerical value that happened before and applying it from a point between the time range\n\n== The key elements of Ichimoku wave movement theory ==\n\nHosoda knew about [[Elliott wave principle]] but his renderings about it were not as complex as Elliott\u2019s. Goichi opted for a simpler version which is focused on pattern detection. Those patterns allowed him to monitor any trend structure but not to define clear target levels or take profits. He classified two main movements:\n\n===Primary movements===\n\n[[File: Primary Waves.png|thumb|Primary waves at Ichimoku]]\n\n===Secondary movements===\n\n[[File: Secondary Waves.png|thumb|Secondary waves at Ichimoku]]\n\n== The key elements of Ichimoku price theory ==\n\nIn order to define target levels, Ichimoku uses 4 different ways to calculate them.\n\n===Value E: most frequent one===\n\n===Value V===\n\n===Value N===\n\n===Value NT: just in case of minor corrections===\n\n[[File:TARGETS.png|thumb|Target levels at Ichimoku]]\n\n== Further Reading ==\n* ''Trading with Ichimoku Clouds: The Essential Guide to Ichimoku Kinko Hyo Technical Analysis'', [[Hoboken, New Jersey]]: [[Wiley_(publisher)|Wiley Trading]]. {{ISBN|9780470609934}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{technical analysis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ichimoku Kinko Hyo}}\n[[Category:Chart overlays]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Market indicators]]\n[[Ca