{"title_page": "Inner Circle of Advocates", "text_new": "{{onesource|date=August 2014}}\n{{Expand section|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Inner Circle of Advocates\n| image = Inner Circle of Advocates logo.png\n| caption = Inner Circle of Advocates logo. The \"7\" refers to the seven-figure verdict originally required for membership\n| formation = 1972\n| founder = [[Richard Grand]]\n| type = [[legal]] [[organization]]\n| location = [[United States]]\n| membership = male members until 1990\n| key_people = [[Judith Livingston]] <small>(first female member)</small>\n}}\nThe '''Inner Circle of Advocates''' is an organization of [[Lawsuit|civil plaintiff]] [[trial lawyer]]s in the [[United States]]. To qualify for an invitation, members must have won a physical injury or death case with a million-dollar verdict.<ref name=\"NYT 1982\" /><ref name=\"Abadinsky2014\">{{cite book|author=Howard Abadinsky|title=Law, Courts, and Justice in America: Seventh Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8V8AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|date=1 May 2014|publisher=Waveland Press|isbn=978-1-4786-2256-7|page=83}}</ref> The group only admitted male members until 1990, when [[Judith Livingston]] became the first female member.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web|last1=Kavilanz|first1=Parija|title=She's the queen of million-dollar verdicts|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/05/15/smallbusiness/judith-livingston-trial-lawyer/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe group was conceived and founded by [[Richard Grand]] in 1972. Membership is limited to 100 lawyers at any one time. However Moorish-American Minister of Jurisprudence AbdAllah El Bey (Canaanland) has assumed occupancy of the executor office.<ref name=\"NYT 1982\">{{cite news|author=David Margolick |title='Inner Circle' Of Lawyers Protects Secrets of Trade|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/08/29/us/inner-circle-of-lawyers-protects-secrets-of-trade.html|work= |date=August 29, 1982 |accessdate=August 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Strong2012\">{{cite book|author=Thomas Strong|title=Strong Advocate: The Life of a Trial Lawyer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5GOeXlAADoC&pg=PA210|date=1 November 2012|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-7296-6|page=210}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.innercircle.org/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Legal organizations based in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{onesource|date=August 2014}}\n{{Expand section|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Inner Circle of Advocates\n| image = Inner Circle of Advocates logo.png\n| caption = Inner Circle of Advocates logo. The \"7\" refers to the seven-figure verdict originally required for membership\n| formation = 1972\n| founder = [[Richard Grand]]\n| type = [[legal]] [[organization]]\n| location = [[United States]]\n| membership = male members until 1990\n| key_people = [[Judith Livingston]] <small>(first female member)</small>\n}}\nThe '''Inner Circle of Advocates''' is an organization of [[Lawsuit|civil plaintiff]] [[trial lawyer]]s in the [[United States]]. To qualify for an invitation, members must have won a physical injury or death case with a million-dollar verdict.<ref name=\"NYT 1982\" /><ref name=\"Abadinsky2014\">{{cite book|author=Howard Abadinsky|title=Law, Courts, and Justice in America: Seventh Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8V8AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|date=1 May 2014|publisher=Waveland Press|isbn=978-1-4786-2256-7|page=83}}</ref> The group only admitted male members until 1990, when [[Judith Livingston]] became the first female member.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web|last1=Kavilanz|first1=Parija|title=She's the queen of million-dollar verdicts|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/05/15/smallbusiness/judith-livingston-trial-lawyer/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe group was conceived and founded by [[Richard Grand]] in 1972. Membership is limited to 100 lawyers at any one time.<ref name=\"NYT 1982\">{{cite news|author=David Margolick |title='Inner Circle' Of Lawyers Protects Secrets of Trade|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/08/29/us/inner-circle-of-lawyers-protects-secrets-of-trade.html|work= |date=August 29, 1982 |accessdate=August 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Strong2012\">{{cite book|author=Thomas Strong|title=Strong Advocate: The Life of a Trial Lawyer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5GOeXlAADoC&pg=PA210|date=1 November 2012|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-7296-6|page=210}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.innercircle.org/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Legal organizations based in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:86e0:1b92:bc95:528f:fcc1:dfde", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I had to add the quote)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_Circle_of_Advocates"}
{"title_page": "Jay Inslee", "text_new": "{{short description|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jay Inslee\n| image = Jay Inslee official portrait.jpg\n| order = 23rd [[List of governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]\n| lieutenant = [[Brad Owen]]<br>[[Cyrus Habib]]\n| predecessor = [[Christine Gregoire]]\n| successor =\n| district2 = {{ushr|WA|4|4th}}\n| predecessor2 = [[Sid Morrison]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| district1 = {{ushr|WA|1|1st}}\n| predecessor1 = [[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]]\n| state1 = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| successor1 = [[Suzan DelBene]]\n| successor2 = [[Doc Hastings]]\n| state2 = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| birth_name = Jay Robert Inslee\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|2|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Trudi Inslee|1972}}\n| children = 3\n| residence = [[Washington Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| term_start = January 16, 2013\n| term_end =\n| term_start1 = January 3, 1999\n| term_end1 = March 20, 2012\n| term_start2 = January 3, 1993\n| term_end2 = January 3, 1995\n| state_house3 = Washington\n| district3 = [[Washington's 14th legislative district|14th legislative]]\n| term_start3 = January 9, 1989\n| term_end3 = January 11, 1993\n| predecessor3 = Jim Lewis\n| successor3 = Dave Lemmon\n| education = [[Stanford University]]<br> [[University of Washington]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Willamette University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Jay Robert Inslee''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u026a|n|z|l|i\u02d0}}; born February 9, 1951) is an American lawyer and politician, who has served as the [[List of Governors of Washington|governor of Washington]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he served in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1993 to 1995 and from 1999 to 2012 and was a [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate from March 1, 2019 to August 21, 2019 for [[2020 United States presidential election|the 2020 election]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Seattle]], Inslee graduated from the [[University of Washington]] and [[Willamette University College of Law]]. He served in the [[Washington House of Representatives]] from 1989 to 1993. In 1992, Inslee was elected to represent {{ushr|WA|4}}, based around [[Central Washington]], in the U.S. House of Representatives. Defeated for reelection in [[1994 United States House of Representatives elections|1994]], Inslee briefly returned to private legal practice. He made his first run for governor of Washington in [[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|1996]], coming in fifth in the [[blanket primary]] ahead of the general election, which was won by Democrat [[Gary Locke]]. Inslee then served as regional director for the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] under President [[Bill Clinton]].\n\nInslee returned to the U.S. House of Representatives in 1999, this time for {{ushr|WA|1|}}. The new district included Seattle's northern suburbs in [[King County, Washington|King County]], [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], and [[Kitsap County, Washington|Kitsap County]]. He was reelected six times before announcing that he would make another run for the governorship in the [[2012 Washington gubernatorial election|2012 election]]. He resigned from Congress to focus on his campaign. He defeated Republican [[Rob McKenna]], the [[List of Attorneys General of Washington|Attorney General of Washington]]. Inslee was reelected to a second term in [[2016 Washington gubernatorial election|2016]], defeating Republican [[Port of Seattle|Seattle Port Commissioner]] [[Bill Bryant (politician)|Bill Bryant]], 54% to 46%. Inslee served as chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|2018 election cycle]].\n\n\n\nInslee [[Jay Inslee 2020 presidential campaign|was a candidate]] for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic nomination]] for President of the United States in the 2020 election, launching his campaign on March 1, 2019. He suspended his campaign on August 21, citing low poll numbers. The next day, Inslee announced his intention to seek a third term as governor in [[2020 Washington gubernatorial election|the 2020 election]].\n\n==Early life, education, and legal career==\nJay Robert Inslee was born February 9, 1951 in Seattle, Washington, the oldest of three sons of Adele A. (n\u00e9e Brown; d. 2007) and Frank E. Inslee (1926\u20132014). His mother worked as a sales clerk at [[Sears]]. His father was a well-known high school counselor and football coach, teaching at [[Tenino, Washington|Tenino High School]], [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]] and [[Chief Sealth International High School|Chief Sealth High School]]. Frank Inslee later became the athletic director for [[Seattle Public Schools]]. Inslee is a fifth-generation Washingtonian.<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Katherine |title=Governor's father, Frank Inslee, dies: teacher, coach, counselor |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/governorrsquos-father-frank-inslee-dies-teacher-coach-counselor/ |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sports\">{{cite news |last1=Garber |first1=Andrew |title=Jay Inslee: Organized sports taught the importance of teamwork |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/jay-inslee-organized-sports-taught-the-importance-of-teamwork/ |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=July 14, 2012}}</ref> Inslee describes his family as being of [[English Americans|English]] and [[Welsh Americans|Welsh]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/family-history-democratic-candidates.html|title=2020 Democrats on Their Family History|date=2019-06-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nInslee attended Seattle's [[Ingraham High School]], where he was an honor-roll student and star athlete, graduating in 1969. He played [[Center (basketball)|center]] on his high school [[basketball]] team, leading them to a state championship title his senior year, and was also the starting [[quarterback]] on his [[American football|football team]].<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref> Inslee's interest in [[environmental issues]] originated at an early age, with his parents leading groups of high school students on trips cleaning [[Mount Rainier]]. He met his future wife, Trudi Tindall, at Ingraham during his sophomore year. Graduating at the height of the [[Vietnam War]], Inslee received [[Conscription in the United States|student deferments from the draft]].<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref name=\"Frank\"/><ref name=\"athlete\">{{cite news |title=Inslee shaped by experience as a high school athlete |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/inslee-shaped-by-experience-as-a-high-school-athlete/281-330698283 |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=King5 |date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nInslee's collegiate career began at [[Stanford University]], where he initially intended to study medicine. After a year he was forced to drop out because he was unable to get a scholarship.<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref>  He returned home and, living in his parents' basement, attended the [[University of Washington]]. He graduated with a B.A. in economics in 1973. He then attended [[Willamette University School of Law]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1976.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref name=\"athlete\" />\n\nInslee and his wife were married on August 27, 1972, and have three sons: Jack, Connor, and Joseph.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Game roster: KIRO vs. Team Inslee |url=http://mynorthwest.com/73456/game-roster-kiro-vs-team-inslee/? |accessdate=January 5, 2019 |publisher=KIRO Radio |date=November 6, 2013}}</ref> After Inslee finished law school, they moved to [[Selah, Washington]]. Inslee joined the law firm Peters, Schmalz, Leadon & Fowler, working as a city prosecutor.<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\" /> He practiced in Selah for 10 years. He first became politically active in 1985, while advocating for the construction of a new high school. The experience sparked Inslee's interest in politics, emboldening him to run for political office.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Raftery |first1=Isolde |title=Jay Inslee's uphill battle |url=https://www.seattlebusinessmag.com/article/jay-inslees-uphill-battle |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |publisher=Seattle Business Magazine |date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Washington House of Representatives (1989\u20131993)==\n\n===Elections===\nInslee ran for the [[Washington House of Representatives]] in 1988 after incumbent Republican State Representative Jim Lewis left office.<ref>{{cite web |title=State of Washington, Members of the Legislature, 1989-2005 |url=http://govinfo.askcarlos.com/wastate/legislators1895-2005.pdf |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> His opponent, Lynn Carmichael, was the former mayor of [[Yakima, Washington|Yakima]] and considered the front-runner in the race. Inslee also struggled to balance his more progressive ideology with the conservative leanings of [[Central Washington]]. His campaign attempted to rectify this by emphasizing his rural upbringing and legal experience supporting local average people, farms and businesses. The [[Washington State Association for Justice|Washington State Trial Lawyers Association]] became Inslee's biggest contributor.<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Craig |title=Inslee's political career took off as Democrat in GOP territory |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/inslees-political-career-took-off-as-democrat-in-gop-territory/ |accessdate=January 7, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=August 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen presented with a potential state budget surplus, Inslee called for a tax cut for the middle class, which Carmichael called irresponsible. Inslee claimed Carmichael had supported a [[sales tax]], which she denied. Inslee was an energetic and active campaigner, benefiting from [[Political campaign|retail politics]].<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\" />\n\nIn the blanket primary, Carmichael ranked first with 43% and Inslee ranked second with 40%. Republican Glen Blomgren ranked third with 17%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=533647 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 - Blanket Primary Race - Sep 20, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, Inslee defeated Carmichael 52%-48%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=407097 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 Race - Nov 08, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> In 1990, Inslee was reelected with 62% of the vote against Republican Ted Mellotte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=325303 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 Race - Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn the Washington state legislature, Inslee pursued a bill to provide initial funding to build five branch campuses of the [[Washington State University]] system. Although the bill failed, his tenacity made an impression on House Speaker Joe King, who said: \"He's not afraid to incur the wrath of the speaker or the caucus.\"<ref>Yakima Herald-Republic, June 11, 1989.</ref> Inslee also focused on preventing [[Doping in sport|steroid usage]] among high school athletes and pushed for a bill requiring all drivers to carry [[vehicle insurance|auto insurance]].<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref> In 1991, he voted for a bill that required the state to devise a cost-effective energy strategy and state agencies and school districts to pursue and maintain energy-efficient operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=HB 1022 - 1991-92 |url=https://app.leg.wa.gov/billsummary?BillNumber=1022&Year=1991 |publisher=[[Washington State Legislature]] |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nInslee served on the Higher Education and Housing Committees.<ref>{{cite news |title=Millions for Migrant Housing Gets Nod |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oaJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G48DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6070,4754598&dq=jay+inslee&hl=en |accessdate=14 January 2020 |work=news.google.com |publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record |date=February 15, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ammons |first1=Dave |title=House Sets Up Showdown on Branch Campuses |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4YxfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9i8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=3090,5038870&dq=jay+inslee&hl=en |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=Lewiston Morning Tribune |date=May 31, 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Congress (1993\u20131995)==\n===Elections===\n;1992\n[[File:Jay Inslee, official 103rd Congress photo.png|thumb|160px|Inslee during the [[103rd United States Congress|103rd Congress]]]]\nIn 1992, six-term incumbent U.S. Representative [[Sid Morrison]] chose not to run for reelection representing {{ushr|Washington|4}}, instead mounting a campaign for governor. Morrison was a popular [[centre-right politics|moderate Republican]] incumbent who was considered successful and well-liked in the Democratic-controlled Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schaefer |first1=David |title=Primary Focus: Governor -- Morrison Takes High Road -- Congressman Hopes It Leads All The Way To State Capital |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19920827&slug=1509537 |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=August 27, 1992}}</ref> Despite initially declining to run, Inslee launched a campaign for the open Congressional seat, based in the central-eastern part of the state. His home area of the district, anchored by Yakima, is relatively rural and agriculture-based, while the southeastern part is more focused on research and nuclear waste disposal, anchored by the [[Tri-Cities, Washington|Tri-Cities]]. Inslee defeated a favored state senator to win the Democratic primary by 1%. Despite the district's conservative lean, Inslee won the general election in an extremely close race.<ref name=\"Political Career\">{{cite news |last1=Gutman |first1=David |title=Jay Inslee's Political Career: From small-town, part-time prosecutor to presidential candidate |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/jay-inslees-political-career-from-part-time-small-town-prosecutor-to-presidential-candidate/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weigel |first1=David |last2=Janes |first2=Chelsea |last3=Wagner |first3=John |title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee joins 2020 Democratic presidential field |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/washington-gov-jay-inslee-joins-2020-democratic-presidential-field/2019/03/01/d44e2366-0e9b-11e9-84fc-d58c33d6c8c7_story.html?noredirect=on |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n;1994\nHe lost his bid for reelection in the [[Republican Revolution]] of 1994 in a rematch against his 1992 opponent, [[Doc Hastings]]. Inslee attributed his 1994 defeat in large part to his vote for the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Postman, Sorrano|first=David, Barbara|title=Former Rep. Jay Inslee Joins Governor's Race|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951129&slug=2155065|accessdate=June 30, 2011|newspaper=Seattle Times|date=November 29, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn Congress, Inslee passed the Yakima River Enhancement Act, a bill long held up in Congress, by brokering a breakthrough with irrigators and wildlife advocates. He also helped to open Japanese markets to American apples and to fund and oversee the nation's biggest nuclear waste site at the [[Hanford Site|Hanford Nuclear Reservation]] near [[Richland, Washington]].<ref name=\"STimes1994\">[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960903&slug=2347250 Inslee Sticks To Campaign Game Plan -- Message Attempts To Boost His Profile], September 3, 1996.</ref><ref name=\"HR 1690\">{{USBill|103|HR|1690|pipe=H.R.1690: To authorize certain elements of the Yakima River Basin Water Enhancement Project, and for other purposes}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GVdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EI8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6322,438162&dq=jay+inslee+committee&hl=en|title=Ellensburg Daily Record - Google News Archive Search|work=google.com}}</ref>\n\n==Inter-congressional years (1995\u20131999)==\nInslee moved to [[Bainbridge Island]], a suburb of [[Seattle]], and briefly resumed the practice of law.<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref>\n\n===1996 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|1996 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nHe ran for [[governor of Washington]] in [[Washington gubernatorial election, 1996|1996]] and lost in the [[blanket primary]]. Democratic [[King County Executive]] and former State Representative [[Gary Locke]] ranked first with 24% of the vote. Democratic [[Mayor of Seattle]] [[Norm Rice]] ranked second with 18%, but didn't qualify for the general election. Republican State Senator [[Ellen Craswell]] ranked third with 15%, and became the Republican candidate in the general election. Republican State Senator and Senate Majority Leader [[Dale Foreman]] ranked fourth with 13%. Inslee ranked fifth with 10%. No other candidate on the ballot received double digits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=18378 |title=WA Governor - All Party Primary Race - Sep 17, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Clinton administration===\nAfter Inslee's failed 1996 bid for [[governor of Washington]], [[President of the United States]] [[Bill Clinton]] appointed him regional director for the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Brian M. |title=Inslee-Clinton fundraiser almost sold out, boasts excited campaign |url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/politicsnorthwest/2012/09/06/inslee-clinton-fundraiser-almost-sold-out-boasts-excited-campaign/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Congress (1999\u20132012)==\n\n===Elections===\nInslee ran again for Congress in 1998, this time in the 1st congressional district against two-term incumbent [[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]]. His campaign attracted national attention when he became the first Democratic candidate to air television ads attacking his opponent and the Republican congressional leadership for the [[Lewinsky scandal]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaji |first1=Mina |last2=Szabo |first2=Christine |title=Jay Inslee: Everything you need to know about the former 2020 presidential candidate |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/jay-inslee/story?id=61305329 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=August 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"lewinskiad\">{{cite news |last1=Bolz |first1=Dan |title=Candidates Are Held Hostage by Scandal |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/campaign101198.htm |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=October 11, 1998}}</ref> Inslee won with 49.8% of the vote to White's 44.1%; he had an unintentional assist in his successful return by the conservative third-party candidacy of Bruce Craswell, husband of 1996 GOP gubernatorial nominee [[Ellen Craswell]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Christie |first1=Tim |title=ELECTION '98: White, Inslee see different reasons for result |url=https://products.kitsapsun.com/archive/1998/11-05/0086_election__98__white__inslee_see_d.html |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |publisher=Kitsap Sun |date=November 5, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Democrat Inslee bests incumbent White for Washington House seat |url=https://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/03/election/house/washington.cd1/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=November 4, 1998}}</ref>\n\nInslee was reelected six times. In 2000, he defeated [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]] Minority Leader Dan McDonald in 2000 with 54.6% of the vote. In 2002, Inslee defeated former state representative Joe Marine with 55.6% of the vote after the district was made more Democratic by redistricting. He never faced another contest that close, and was reelected three more times with over 60% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |title=The 2000 Campaign: Washington State;Primary Vote Bolsters House Democrat G.O.P. Saw As Vulnerable |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/02/us/2000-campaign-washington-state-primary-vote-bolsters-house-democrat-gop-saw.html |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=October 2, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"Inslee Results\">{{cite news |title=Inslee challengers look to curb spending |url=https://www.bainbridgereview.com/news/inslee-challengers-look-to-curb-spending/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=Bainbridge Island Review |date=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, after [[Gary Locke]] announced he would not seek a third term as Washington's governor, Inslee briefly flirted with a gubernatorial bid before deciding to remain in Congress.<ref name=\"inslee4gov\">[http://www.seattlepi.com/local/138758_governor09.html Inslee Won't Run For Governor], Joel Connelly, Seattle Post Intelligencer, September 8, 2003.</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009-10 campaign cycle, Inslee raised $1,140,025. In data compiled for the period 2005 to 2007 and excluding individual contributions of less than $200, 64 percent of Inslee's donations were from outside the state of Washington and 86 percent came from outside his district (compared to 79 percent for the average House member). 43 percent of Inslee's donations came from Washington, D.C., Virginia and Maryland. The largest interests funding Inslee's campaign were pharmaceutical and health-related companies, lawyers and law firms, and high-tech companies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Campaign Funding Sources|url=http://maplight.org/us-congress/legislator/297-jay-inslee|work=Inslee Contributions Illuminated|publisher=maplight.org|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Inslee Results\"/>\n\nIn 2010 he won by a 15-point margin, with 57.67% of the votes cast in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=Congressional District 1|url=http://vote.wa.gov/Elections/WEI/Results.aspx?ElectionID=37&JurisdictionTypeID=3&JurisdictionID=103&ViewMode=Results|work=2010 Election Results|publisher=Washington Secretary of State|accessdate=June 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321001943/http://vote.wa.gov/Elections/WEI/Results.aspx?ElectionID=37&JurisdictionTypeID=3&JurisdictionID=103&ViewMode=Results|archivedate=March 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Inslees and the Dalai Lama.jpg|thumb|Jay Inslee and his wife Trudi Inslee met with the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] in 2008.]]\nAs a member of the centrist [[New Democrat Coalition]], Inslee accumulated expertise on high-tech issues and vocally supported policies combating climate change.<ref name=\"STTech\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/techtracks/archives/2007/03/inslee_bill_would_push_fcc_on_white_space_decision.html|title=The Seattle Times: Tech Tracks|work=nwsource.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118135626/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/techtracks/archives/2007/03/inslee_bill_would_push_fcc_on_white_space_decision.html|archivedate=November 18, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"NDC\">{{cite news |title=Jay Inslee, with Climate Change Agenda, Running for President |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/03/01/jay-inslee-climate-change-democrat-president/ |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=The Mercury News |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nInslee was awarded a \"Friend of the National Parks\" award by the [[National Parks Conservation Association]] (NPCA) in 2001 for his support of legislation protecting the integrity and quality of the [[National Park System]].<ref name=\"NPCAfriend\">[http://www.npca.org/media_center/press_releases/2001/page-27598936.html Friend of the National Parks Award Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121111738/http://www.npca.org/media_center/press_releases/2001/page-27598936.html |date=November 21, 2008 }}, [[National Parks Conservation Association]], February 15, 2001</ref>\n\nInslee was \"one of Congress's most ardent advocates of strong action to combat global warming,\" according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=At House E.P.A. Hearing, Both Sides Claim Science |last=Broder |first=John M. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/science/earth/09climate.html |date=March 9, 2011 |page=17 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> He was the first public figure to propose an Apollo-like energy program, in an opinion editorial in the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' on December 19, 2002 and a series of similar pieces in other publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/opinion/100516_inslee19.shtml|title=New Apollo Project can help us unplug our need for oil|work=seattlepi.com}}</ref> Inslee co-authored ''[[Apollo's Fire (book)|Apollo's Fire: Igniting America's Clean Energy Economy]]'', in which he argues that through improved federal policies the United States can wean itself off foreign oil and [[fossil fuel]], create millions of [[green-collar]] jobs, and stop [[global warming]]. He has been a prominent supporter of the Apollo Alliance.<ref name=\"ApolloAlliance\">[http://www.apolloalliance.org/resources_100mpg.php Inslee articles at the Apollo Alliance web page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126233311/http://www.apolloalliance.org/resources_100mpg.php |date=November 26, 2008 }}</ref> Inslee strongly believes the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] should remain authorized to regulate [[greenhouse gas]] emissions. In a 2011 House hearing on the [[Energy Tax Prevention Act]], he said Republicans have \"an allergy to science and scientists\" during a discussion of whether the [[regulation of greenhouse gases under the Clean Air Act]] should remain in place following a controversial court finding on the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wing|first=Nick|title=Jay Inslee: Republicans Suffer From 'Allergy To Science And Scientists'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/09/jay-inslee-gop-allergy-science_n_833404.html|work=Huffpost Politics|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 1, 2011|date=March 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nInslee was an outspoken critic of the [[George W. Bush]] administration's [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. On July 31, 2007, he introduced legislation calling for an inquiry to determine whether then [[United States Attorney General]] [[Alberto Gonzales]] should be impeached. Gonzales eventually resigned.<ref name=\"LATimes20070801A\">[[Associated Press]], [https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/politics/la-na-impeach1aug01,1,130274.story?coll=la-news-politics-national&track=crosspromo ''Bill calls for Gonzales impeachment inquiry''], [[Los Angeles Times]], August 1, 2007</ref>\n\nStill an avid basketball player and fan, Inslee identified as a member of \"Hoopaholics\", a charity group dedicated to \"treatment of old guys addicted to basketball and who can no longer jump\", as Inslee has often joked.<ref name=\"hoopaholics\">[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/highschoolsports/2003867146_flashback04.html \"Flashback | Political football now Inslee's game], Seattle Times, September 4, 2007.</ref> In October 2009, he played basketball at the White House in a series of games featuring members of Congress on one team and members of the administration, including President Obama, on the other.<ref>{{cite news|last=Daly |first=Matthew |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2010027342_apusobamabasketballcongress.html |title=Local News &#124; Lawmakers play hoops with Obama at White House &#124; Seattle Times Newspaper |publisher=Seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=October 8, 2009 |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nInslee voted for the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], the federal health care law.<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 165 |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll165.xml |publisher=[[Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|Clerk of the US House of Representatives]] |date=March 21, 2010 |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Inslee voted in favor of authorizing the use of U.S. armed forces in the [[2011 Libyan civil war]] and against limiting the use of funds to support [[NATO]]'s [[2011 military intervention in Libya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congress Votes on Libya|url=http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400193_jay_inslee|work=Inslee Supports Adventure in Libya|publisher=OpenCongress.org|accessdate=July 1, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701094839/http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400193_Jay_Inslee|archivedate=July 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nInslee was once touted as a candidate for [[United States Secretary of the Interior]] and for [[United States Secretary of Energy]] during the [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"interiorapt\">[http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/politicsnorthwest/2008/10/31/inslee_for_interior_secretary.html Inslee For Interior Secretary?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126133645/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/politicsnorthwest/2008/10/31/inslee_for_interior_secretary.html|date=January 26, 2009}} Seattle Times, October 31, 2008</ref><ref name=\"DOEapt\">[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/energywire/2008/11/obamas_energy_department.html Obama's Energy Department] Newsweek/Washington Post EnergyWire, Steve Mufson, November 6, 2008</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2012, Inslee left Congress to focus on his campaign for governor of Washington.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Song |first1=Kyung M. |title=Inslee leaving U.S. House but still eligible for pension |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/inslee-leaving-us-house-but-still-eligible-for-pension/ |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Friends of Animals Caucus\n* Congressional Internet Caucus\n* House Medicare and Medicaid Fairness Caucus\n* House Oceans Caucus\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]\n* Congressional Arts Caucus\n* Sustainable Energy and Environment Coalition\n\n==Governor of Washington (2013\u2013present)==\n\n===2012 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|2012 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nOn June 27, 2011, Inslee announced his candidacy for governor of Washington.<ref name=\"insleeannounces\">[http://kuow.org/program.php?id=23805 Inslee Announces Run For Governor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015020823/http://kuow.org/program.php?id=23805 |date=October 15, 2011 }}, Liz Jones, KUOW, June 28, 2011.</ref> His campaign focused on job creation, outlining dozens of proposals to increase job growth in clean energy, the aerospace industry, and biotechnology. He also supported a ballot measure to legalize gay marriage, which passed, and opposed tax increases.<ref name=\"won'tconcede\">[http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019621861_elexgovernor07m.html Inslee takes strong lead, but McKenna won't concede], Jim Brunner, Seattle Times, November 7, 2012.</ref> He won election with 51% of the vote, a three-point margin over his Republican opponent, [[Rob McKenna]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=WA STATE Gubernatorial results|url=http://sos.wa.gov|publisher=WA STATE SEC OF STATE|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130223191448/http://sos.wa.gov/|archivedate=February 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2016 gubernatorial election===\n{{main|2016 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nIn December 2015, Inslee announced on Washington's public affairs TV channel [[TVW (Washington)|TVW]] that he would run for a second term as governor. He emphasized increased spending on transportation and education as his primary first-term accomplishment, though he had struggled to work with the Republican-controlled [[Majority Coalition Caucus]] in the State Senate.<ref name=\"NWNews\">{{cite news |last1=Jenkins |first1=Austin |title=Inslee Vs. Bryant: A Preview Of The 2016 Washington Gubernatorial Face-Off |url=https://www.nwnewsnetwork.org/post/inslee-vs-bryant-preview-2016-washington-gubernatorial-face |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=NW News Network |date=December 9, 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the general election Inslee faced former Port of Seattle Commissioner [[Bill Bryant (politician)|Bill Bryant]]. The primary issues of the campaign were [[climate change]], job creation, [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum wage]], and [[Capital gains tax|capital gains taxes]]. Inslee far outraised Bryant,<ref name=\"Win Second\"/><ref name=\"NWNews\"/><ref name=\"King5\"/> and was reelected in November with 54% of the vote.<ref name=\"Win Second\">{{cite news |last1=Wissel |first1=Paula |title=Gov. Jay Inslee Defeats Bill Bryant To Win Second Term |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/washington-governor-jay-inslee-bill-bryant/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KNKX News |date=November 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inslee defeats Bryant in Wash. Governor race |url=https://www.kxly.com/inslee-defeats-bryant-in-wash-governor-race/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KXLY |date=November 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"King5\">{{cite news |title=Wash. Governor Inslee wins second term |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/wash-governor-inslee-wins-second-term/281-348472289 |accessdate=January 5, 2019 |publisher=KING5 |date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2020 gubernatorial election===\n{{main|2020 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nOn March 1, 2019, Inslee announced he would run for president, but kept open the possibility of running for a third term if his presidential campaign failed. Several potential Democratic gubernatorial candidates, including state Attorney General [[Bob Ferguson (politician)|Bob Ferguson]], Commissioner of Public Lands [[Hilary Franz]], and King County Executive [[Dow Constantine]], were all waiting to announce campaigns until Inslee made his decision.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oxley |first1=Dyer |title=What will they do now that Jay Inslee is running for governor again? |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1488696/constantine-ferguson-franz-governor-inslee/? |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=MYNorthwest |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> As Inslee's presidential campaign failed to gain traction during the summer of 2019, he was pressured to drop out and make his gubernatorial plans clear to the other potential candidates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kruse |first1=Brandi |title=It\u2019s decision time for Washington Governor Jay Inslee |url=https://q13fox.com/2019/08/20/its-decision-time-for-washington-governor-jay-inslee/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=Q13 FOX |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> On August 21, 2019, Inslee dropped out of the presidential campaign and announced the next day he would run for reelection as governor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gottlieb |first1=Paul |title=If Jay Inslee leaves governor job, AG Bob Ferguson may run |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/northwest/if-jay-inslee-leaves-governor-job-ag-bob-ferguson-may-run/ |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |publisher=Everett Herald |date=May 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"USA 3rd\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Kip |title=Gov. Jay Inslee announces re-election bid; AG Bob Ferguson also will seek re-election |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2019/aug/22/gov-jay-inslee-announces-re-election-bid-ag-bob-fe/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=The Spokesman-Review |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2020, Inslee's major opponents in the election are State Senator [[Phil Fortunato]]; [[Republic, Washington]] police chief Loren Culp; and former [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] mayor Joshua Freed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennings |first1=Nicole |title=Gubernatorial candidate Joshua Freed walks a middle line for homelessness |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1509750/dori-joshua-freed/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KIRO Radio |date=September 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Former Bothell mayor announces gubernatorial run |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/former-bothell-mayor-announces-gubernatorial-run/281-5c792fb2-a48a-487d-afe2-d4aff379034c |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KING5 |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== First term: 2013\u20132017 ===\nDuring the 2013 session, the [[Washington State Legislature|legislature]] failed to create a fiscal budget plan during the initial session, and Inslee was forced to call two special sessions to provide time for a budget to be created. The Republican-controlled [[Washington State Senate|Senate]] and Democratic-controlled [[Washington State House of Representatives|House]] each passed its own budget and could not agree on one.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee calls second special session|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/06/washington_gov_jay_inslee_call_1.html|newspaper=Oregon Live|date=June 11, 2013}}</ref> Finally, in June 2013, Inslee signed a $33.6 billion budget to which both houses had agreed as a compromise. The budget increased funding for education by $1 billion. It also adjusted [[property tax|property taxes]] and [[tax break|tax breaks]] in order to increase state revenue by $1 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Mike |title=A look inside Washington state's $33.6 billion budget plan |url=https://komonews.com/news/local/a-look-inside-washington-states-336-billion-budget-plan-11-20-2015 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KOMO News |date=June 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2013, Inslee signed an additional [[estate tax]] into law. The tax had bipartisan support, and passed the Senate, 30\u201319.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee signs estate tax fix into law|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/06/washington_gov_jay_inslee_sign.html|newspaper=Oregon Live|date=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jay Inslee Speech (8724201105).jpg|thumb|left|Inslee giving a speech regarding [[Boeing]] in May 2013]]\nIn December 2013, Inslee was elected to serve as finance chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Burns|first=Alexander|title=DGA appoints leaders for 2014|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/dga-appoints-leaders-for-2014-100877.html?hp=f1|publisher=Politico|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, Inslee gave a speech commending machinists who voted to renew [[Boeing]]'s contract with Seattle area union employees, allowing the company to build its [[Boeing 777X|Boeing 777x]] aircraft [[Boeing Everett Factory|in Everett]]. He said the contract would bring Washington to a new industrial plateau and be a turning point for Washington jobs:\n\n<blockquote>These jobs are in the thousands and it is not only on the 777X, the first model of the 777X, but all the subsequent derivative models as well.</blockquote>\n\nThe plan was to prevent Boeing from building part of the aircraft in Washington and part of it elsewhere, as they did with the [[Boeing 787]], which was partially constructed in [[South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Hana|title=Governor Inslee says Boeing deal could open new industrial plateau|url=http://q13fox.com/2014/01/04/governor-inslee-says-boeing-deal-could-open-new-industrial-plateau/#axzz2pVAPMUv4|newspaper=Q13 Fox|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boeing pact with Machinists union called turning point for labor|url=http://triblive.com/business/headlines/5360816-74/boeing-union-state#axzz2pVAQFg9d|newspaper=TribLive|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2014, Inslee announced a [[Moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on [[Capital punishment in Washington state|executions in Washington]]:\n\n<blockquote>There have been too many doubts raised about capital punishment, there are too many flaws in this system today. There is too much at stake to accept an imperfect system.</blockquote>\n\nInslee cited the high cost of pursuing the death penalty, the randomness with which it is sought, and the lack of evidence that it is a deterrent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inslee halts executions in state while he is governor|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2022883256_deathpenaltyinsleexml.html|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Washington state to suspend death penalty by governor's moratorium|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/11/washington-state-death-penalty-governor-inslee-suspends|newspaper=The Guardian|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Second term: 2017\u2013present ===\nInslee began his second term in January 2017, proposing full funding of state education (in compliance with the [[McCleary decision]]) and addressing mental health needs while also raising worker pay.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Sullivan |first=Joseph |date=January 9, 2017 |title=State lawmakers face tough fight over education funding as legislative session opens |page=B1 |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/state-lawmakers-face-tough-fight-over-education-funding-as-legislative-session-opens/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> After newly inaugurated President [[Donald Trump]] signed an [[Executive Order 13769|executive order on January 27 banning people from seven Muslim-majority countries from entering the United States]], Inslee and Attorney General [[Bob Ferguson (politician)|Bob Ferguson]] announced their intention to sue Trump, alleging his order was unconstitutional. The civil action, ''[[Washington v. Trump]]'', was filed on January 30 and on February 3 successfully earned a [[temporary restraining order]] to forbid federal enforcement of some of the ban's provisions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Burns |first=Alexander |date=January 30, 2017 |title=Legal Challenges Mount Against Trump's Travel Ban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/30/us/legal-challenges-mount-against-trumps-travel-ban.html?_r=0 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Burns |first=Alexander |date=February 4, 2017 |title=How Washington State Upended Trump's Travel Ban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/trump-travel-ban-washington-seattle-ferguson.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> An appeal and request to stay filed by the federal government was subsequently denied by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]. Inslee and Ferguson declared victory over Trump on February 16, after his administration announced it would revise the travel ban to comply with the court decisions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dolan |first1=Maura |last2=Kaleem |first2=Jaweed |date=February 16, 2017 |title=Trump says he will issue a new order after a 'very bad decision' blocked his initial travel ban |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-travel-executive-order-20170216-story.html |work=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Inslee garnered national media attention during the lawsuit.<ref name=\"seattletimes_inslees_profile\">{{cite news |last=Brunner |first=Jim |date=February 21, 2017 |title=Jay Inslee for president? Governor's profile is on the rise |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/inslees-profile-lifted-with-states-legal-victories-on-immigration/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2017 legislative session, the [[Washington State Legislature]] failed to pass a state operating budget by the end of its regular session on April 25, so Inslee called for a 30-day special session. The legislature again failed to pass a budget during that session, forcing Inslee to call a third one, beginning June 22. As the state's fiscal year ends on June 30, a [[Government shutdowns in the United States|partial government shutdown]] was feared.<ref>{{cite news |last1=La Corte |first1=Rachel |title=No end in sight as Washington lawmakers edge toward a third special session |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/may/23/washington-legislatures-first-special-session-ends/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> Conflict over resource allocation between [[Rural areas in the United States|rural areas]] and [[United States urban area|urban areas]] was a major reason for the impasse. The [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]] passed a budget on June 30 and Inslee signed it into law shortly after 11 pm. Its specifics were still being released several hours after it was enacted. Lawmakers critiqued the haste with which the budget was considered and passed, having received the 616-page document only that day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Camden |first1=Jim |title=Legislature passes $43.7 billion budget, and taxes to pay for it; Inslee signs before midnight |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/jun/30/437-billion-washington-budget-begins-push-through-/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> By the end of the third session on July 20, the legislature had still failed to pass a [[Capital budgeting|capital budget]] concerning long-term goals and improvements.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brand |first1=Natalie |last2=Graf |first2=Heather |title=Washington lawmakers adjourn with no capital budget |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/washington-lawmakers-adjourn-with-no-capital-budget/281-458374474 |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=King5 |date=July 20, 2017}}</ref> This was the third time during Inslee's tenure the state's budget was passed in the last week of the legislative session.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Melissa |title=Threat of shutdown looms as Legislature heads into triple overtime over budget |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article157434149.html |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |agency=The News Tribune |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017 Inslee awarded $6.4 million in grant funding for apprenticeships and career connections to 29,000 youth in 11 communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/wagovernor/inslee-awards-6-4-129c4de96df3|title=Inslee awards $6 million to create apprenticeship and career connections for 29,000 youth in 11 communities|date=December 8, 2017|website=Medium}}</ref> He called this initiative [https://careerconnectwa.org/ Career Connect Washington]. It includes a Task Force and several prominent stakeholder groups including [[Alaska Airlines]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Boeing]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Kaiser Permanente]]. Career Connect Washington has established new apprenticeship opportunities, including the [https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/education/article143777889.html Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Committee]'s registered Youth Apprenticeship program for high school students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtb.wa.gov/careerconnectwa.asp|title=Career Connected Washington Task Force|website=Workforce Training & Education Board}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/washington-voters-dont-think-schools-prepare-kids-for-careers-the-state-is-trying-to-change-that/|title=Washington voters don't think schools prepare kids for careers. The state is trying to change that.|date=October 31, 2018|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=November 16, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nInslee served as chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2018|2018 election cycle]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mycolumbiabasin.com/2017/12/04/washington-governor-elected-next-dga-chair/|title=Washington governor elected next DGA chair|date=December 4, 2017|work=My Columbia Basin|access-date=December 5, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> in which Democrats gained seven net governorships nationwide.<ref name=\"theatlantic_201901\">{{cite news |last1=Dovere |first1=Edward-Isaac |title=Jay Inslee Is Betting He Can Win the Presidency on Climate Change |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/01/washington-governor-jay-inslee-running-president/579217/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Atlantic |date=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Inslee announced new legislation aimed at reducing the state's carbon emissions over approximately two decades. It would effectively require Washington utilities to end the use of fossil fuels by mid-century, making Washington \"adopt a clean fuel standard\", \"promote electric and low-emission vehicles\", and \"provide incentives to renovate existing buildings to reduce\" emissions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Reid |title=Washington governor plans major climate initiatives |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/420611-washington-governor-plans-major-climate-initiatives |website=The Hill |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Inslee said he would provide an expedited process for approximately 3,500 people convicted of small-time cannabis possession to apply for and receive pardons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/legal-pot/washington-gov-inslee-pardon-thousands-convicted-marijuana-possession-n954981|title=Washington Gov. Inslee to pardon thousands convicted of marijuana possession|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March and April 2020, Inslee ordered significant social distancing measures statewide, including banning large events, a stay-at-home order, and the closing of all schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/inslee-extends-stay-home-stay-healthy-through-may-4|title=Inslee extends 'Stay Home, Stay Healthy' through May 4 {{!}} Governor Jay Inslee|website=www.governor.wa.gov|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{main|Jay Inslee 2020 presidential campaign}}\n[[File:Jay Inslee presidential announcement - March 1, 2019 - 01 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Inslee declaring his candidacy for president]]\n\nThroughout 2018, speculation rose that Inslee might run for [[President of the United States]] in [[2020 United States presidential election|the 2020 election]]. He garnered national attention because of ''[[Washington v. Trump]],'' a lawsuit challenging the [[Trump Administration|Trump Administration's]] [[Executive Order 13769|order to ban people from seven Muslim-majority countries from entering the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wang |first=Amy B. |date=February 5, 2017 |title=How Washington state became the epicenter of resistance to Trump's agenda |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/02/05/how-washington-state-became-the-epicenter-of-resistance-to-trumps-agenda/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"seattletimes_inslees_profile\"/> While Inslee was chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]], Democrats gained seven net governorships in [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|the 2018 gubernatorial elections]], further propelling him into the national spotlight and fueling speculation that he would run.<ref name=\"theatlantic_201901\"/> Inslee cited [[climate change]] as his primary motivation for running, strongly criticizing the Trump Administration's policies.<ref name=\"Inslee-presidential-2020\">{{cite news|last=Brunner|first=Jim|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/gov-jay-inslees-new-pac-raises-112000-as-he-actively-considers-presidential-run/|title=Gov. Jay Inslee's new PAC raises $112,000 as he 'actively' considers presidential run|date=December 6, 2018|work=[[Seattle Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, reports surfaced that Inslee was beginning to form an [[exploratory committee]], the first step in a campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kroll |first1=Andy |title=Jay Inslee, the 'Climate Candidate,' Joins the 2020 Race |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/jay-inslee-2020-774051/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=January 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/01/washington-governor-jay-inslee-running-president/579217/|title=Jay Inslee Is Betting He Can Win the Presidency on Climate Change|last=Dovere|first=Edward-Isaac|date=January 2, 2019|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=January 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/jay-inslee-is-running-for-president-governor-of-washington/|title=Jay Inslee Is Running For President \u2014 You Know, the Governor of Washington|date=January 2, 2019|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=January 2, 2019}}</ref> Inslee was a [[dark horse|dark-horse]] candidate; initially, he was rarely included in [[Opinion polling for the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|polling for the primary]], was not well known outside Washington, and made few trips to early primary states such as Iowa and New Hampshire. But he pointed to former Presidents [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Bill Clinton]], calling them \"pretty much unknown governors of small states\" and adding, \"this is a wide-open field. No one has a lock on this. No one has a total crystal ball as to what the nation wants.\"<ref name=\"Inslee-presidential-2020\" />\n\nInslee announced his candidacy for president on March 1, 2019, saying he would focus on combating climate change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.cnn.com/en/article/h_938905d87233bde443acdaa78523780d|title=CNN - Breaking News, Latest News and Videos|website=m.cnn.com|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> His campaign requested a debate focused on climate change. The [[Democratic National Committee]] denied the request, but 53 of its voting members wrote an open letter protesting that decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/05/politics/jay-inslee-climate-change-cnntv/index.html|title=Inslee: DNC rejecting climate change debate is \"extremely disappointing\"|first=Kate|last=Sullivan|publisher=CNN|date=2019-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/53-voting-dnc-members-protest-rejection-jay-inslees-climate-change-debate-4274c1fc-eae4-4d88-9757-f62ad3200667.html|title=53 DNC members protest rejection of Jay Inslee's climate change debate|first=Orion|last=Rummier|publisher=Axios|date=2019-06-08|accessdate=2019-06-08}}</ref>\n\nFacing poor polling numbers and seeing no path to victory, Inslee announced the suspension of his campaign on ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' on August 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jay Inslee, governor who centered climate change in presidential race, drops out of the contest |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/08/22/jay-inslee-governor-who-centered-climate-change-presidential-race-drops-out-contest/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Inslee, exiting the presidential race, reflects on his campaign|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2019/8/21/20826258/jay-inslee-presidential-exit-interview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|accessdate=August 21, 2019|date=August 21, 2019|author=David Roberts}}</ref> The next day, he announced he would run for a third term as governor in [[2020 Washington gubernatorial election|the 2020 election]].<ref name=\"USA 3rd\">{{cite news |last1=Santucci |first1=Jeanine |title=Jay Inslee begins campaign for 3rd term as governor after dropping out of presidential race |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/22/jay-inslee-seek-3rd-washington-governor-term-after-ending-2020-bid/2087537001/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=USA Today |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Jay Inslee}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date || Position || Status || Opponent || Result || Vote share || Opponent vote share\n|-\n| 1988 || WA Representative || Open seat || || Elected || ||\n|-\n| 1990 || WA Representative || Incumbent || || Re-elected || ||\n|-\n| 1992 || U.S. Representative || Open seat || [[Doc Hastings]] (R) || Elected || 51% || 49%\n|-\n| 1994 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || [[Doc Hastings]] (R) || Defeated || 47% || 53%\n|-\n| 1996 || WA Governor || Open seat primary || [[Gary Locke]] (D), others || Defeated ||10%\n|\n|-\n| 1998 || U.S. Representative || Challenger || [[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]] (R) || Elected || 50% || 44%\n|-\n| 2000 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || Dan McDonald (R) || Re-elected || 55% || 43%\n|-\n| 2002 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || Joe Marine (R) || Re-elected || 56% || 41%\n|-\n| 2004 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || Randy Eastwood (R) || Re-elected || 62% || 36%\n|-\n| 2006 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || Larry W. Ishmael (R) || Re-elected || 68% || 32%\n|-\n| 2008 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || Larry W. Ishmael (R) || Re-elected || 68% || 32%\n|-\n| 2010 || U.S. Representative || Incumbent || James Watkins (R) || Re-elected || 57% || 43%\n|-\n| 2012 || WA Governor || Open seat || [[Rob McKenna]] (R) || Elected || 51% || 49%\n|-\n| 2016 || WA Governor || Incumbent || [[Bill Bryant (politician)|Bill Bryant]] (R) || Re-elected || 54% ||46%\n|}\n\n==Works==\n* Jay Inslee and Bracken Hendricks, ''Apollo's Fire: Igniting America's Clean Energy Economy'', [[Island Press]] (October 1, 2007), {{ISBN|978-1-59726-175-3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.governor.wa.gov/ Governor Jay Inslee] - Official website from the [[Government of the State of Washington]]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Government/Executive/Governor_Jay_Inslee}}\n* [http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=I000026 Profile] at the ''[[Biographical Directory of the United States Congress]]''\n* {{C-SPAN|jayinslee}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sid Morrison]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Washington|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Washington's 4th congressional district]]|years=1993\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Doc Hastings]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Washington|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Washington's 1st congressional district]]|years=1999\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Suzan DelBene]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]|years=[[Washington gubernatorial election, 2012|2012]], [[Washington gubernatorial election, 2016|2016]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gina Raimondo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Washington]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Washington|rows=2}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]]|as=[[Governor of Montana]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Washington}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brad Little]]|as=[[Governor of Idaho]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Washington}}\n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Current statewide political officials of Washington}}\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inslee, Jay}}\n[[Category:Jay Inslee]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American Protestants]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Washington House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People associated with energy]]\n[[Category:People from Selah, Washington]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Washington College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Willamette University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jay Inslee\n| image = Jay Inslee official portrait.jpg\n| order = 23rd [[List of governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]\n| lieutenant = [[Brad Owen]]<br>[[Cyrus Habib]]\n| predecessor = [[Christine Gregoire]]\n| successor =\n| district2 = {{ushr|WA|4|4th}}\n| predecessor2 = [[Sid Morrison]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| district1 = {{ushr|WA|1|1st}}\n| predecessor1 = [[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]]\n| state1 = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| successor1 = [[Suzan DelBene]]\n| successor2 = [[Doc Hastings]]\n| state2 = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| birth_name = Jay Robert Inslee\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|2|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Trudi Inslee|1972}}\n| children = 3\n| residence = [[Washington Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| term_start = January 16, 2013\n| term_end =\n| term_start1 = January 3, 1999\n| term_end1 = March 20, 2012\n| term_start2 = January 3, 1993\n| term_end2 = January 3, 1995\n| state_house3 = Washington\n| district3 = [[Washington's 14th legislative district|14th legislative]]\n| term_start3 = January 9, 1989\n| term_end3 = January 11, 1993\n| predecessor3 = Jim Lewis\n| successor3 = Dave Lemmon\n| education = [[Stanford University]]<br> [[University of Washington]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Willamette University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Jay Robert Inslee''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u026a|n|z|l|i\u02d0}}; born February 9, 1951) is an American lawyer and politician, who has served as the [[List of Governors of Washington|governor of Washington]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he served in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1993 to 1995 and from 1999 to 2012 and was a [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate from March 1, 2019 to August 21, 2019 for [[2020 United States presidential election|the 2020 election]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Seattle]], Inslee graduated from the [[University of Washington]] and [[Willamette University College of Law]]. He served in the [[Washington House of Representatives]] from 1989 to 1993. In 1992, Inslee was elected to represent {{ushr|WA|4}}, based around [[Central Washington]], in the U.S. House of Representatives. Defeated for reelection in [[1994 United States House of Representatives elections|1994]], Inslee briefly returned to private legal practice. He made his first run for governor of Washington in [[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|1996]], coming in fifth in the [[blanket primary]] ahead of the general election, which was won by Democrat [[Gary Locke]]. Inslee then served as regional director for the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] under President [[Bill Clinton]].\n\nInslee returned to the U.S. House of Representatives in 1999, this time for {{ushr|WA|1|}}. The new district included Seattle's northern suburbs in [[King County, Washington|King County]], [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], and [[Kitsap County, Washington|Kitsap County]]. He was reelected six times before announcing that he would make another run for the governorship in the [[2012 Washington gubernatorial election|2012 election]]. He resigned from Congress to focus on his campaign. He defeated Republican [[Rob McKenna]], the [[List of Attorneys General of Washington|Attorney General of Washington]]. Inslee was reelected to a second term in [[2016 Washington gubernatorial election|2016]], defeating Republican [[Port of Seattle|Seattle Port Commissioner]] [[Bill Bryant (politician)|Bill Bryant]], 54% to 46%. Inslee served as chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|2018 election cycle]].\n\nAs governor, Inslee has emphasized [[climate change]], [[Education in the United States|education]] and [[drug policy reform]]. He has garnered national attention for his critiques of President [[Donald Trump]]. Inslee, State Attorney General [[Bob Ferguson (politician)|Bob Ferguson]] and State Solicitor General [[Noah Purcell]] sued the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump Administration]] over [[Executive Order 13769]], which halted travel for 90 days from seven Muslim-majority countries and imposed a total ban on Syrian refugees entering the United States. The case, ''[[Washington v. Trump]]'', led to the order being blocked by the courts, and other executive orders later superseded it.\n\nInslee [[Jay Inslee 2020 presidential campaign|was a candidate]] for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic nomination]] for President of the United States in the 2020 election, launching his campaign on March 1, 2019. He suspended his campaign on August 21, citing low poll numbers. The next day, Inslee announced his intention to seek a third term as governor in [[2020 Washington gubernatorial election|the 2020 election]].\n\n==Early life, education, and legal career==\nJay Robert Inslee was born February 9, 1951 in Seattle, Washington, the oldest of three sons of Adele A. (n\u00e9e Brown; d. 2007) and Frank E. Inslee (1926\u20132014). His mother worked as a sales clerk at [[Sears]]. His father was a well-known high school counselor and football coach, teaching at [[Tenino, Washington|Tenino High School]], [[Garfield High School (Seattle)|Garfield High School]] and [[Chief Sealth International High School|Chief Sealth High School]]. Frank Inslee later became the athletic director for [[Seattle Public Schools]]. Inslee is a fifth-generation Washingtonian.<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Katherine |title=Governor's father, Frank Inslee, dies: teacher, coach, counselor |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/governorrsquos-father-frank-inslee-dies-teacher-coach-counselor/ |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sports\">{{cite news |last1=Garber |first1=Andrew |title=Jay Inslee: Organized sports taught the importance of teamwork |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/jay-inslee-organized-sports-taught-the-importance-of-teamwork/ |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=July 14, 2012}}</ref> Inslee describes his family as being of [[English Americans|English]] and [[Welsh Americans|Welsh]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/family-history-democratic-candidates.html|title=2020 Democrats on Their Family History|date=2019-06-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nInslee attended Seattle's [[Ingraham High School]], where he was an honor-roll student and star athlete, graduating in 1969. He played [[Center (basketball)|center]] on his high school [[basketball]] team, leading them to a state championship title his senior year, and was also the starting [[quarterback]] on his [[American football|football team]].<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref> Inslee's interest in [[environmental issues]] originated at an early age, with his parents leading groups of high school students on trips cleaning [[Mount Rainier]]. He met his future wife, Trudi Tindall, at Ingraham during his sophomore year. Graduating at the height of the [[Vietnam War]], Inslee received [[Conscription in the United States|student deferments from the draft]].<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref name=\"Frank\"/><ref name=\"athlete\">{{cite news |title=Inslee shaped by experience as a high school athlete |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/inslee-shaped-by-experience-as-a-high-school-athlete/281-330698283 |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |publisher=King5 |date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nInslee's collegiate career began at [[Stanford University]], where he initially intended to study medicine. After a year he was forced to drop out because he was unable to get a scholarship.<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref>  He returned home and, living in his parents' basement, attended the [[University of Washington]]. He graduated with a B.A. in economics in 1973. He then attended [[Willamette University School of Law]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1976.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref name=\"athlete\" />\n\nInslee and his wife were married on August 27, 1972, and have three sons: Jack, Connor, and Joseph.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Game roster: KIRO vs. Team Inslee |url=http://mynorthwest.com/73456/game-roster-kiro-vs-team-inslee/? |accessdate=January 5, 2019 |publisher=KIRO Radio |date=November 6, 2013}}</ref> After Inslee finished law school, they moved to [[Selah, Washington]]. Inslee joined the law firm Peters, Schmalz, Leadon & Fowler, working as a city prosecutor.<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\" /> He practiced in Selah for 10 years. He first became politically active in 1985, while advocating for the construction of a new high school. The experience sparked Inslee's interest in politics, emboldening him to run for political office.<ref name=\"Sports\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Raftery |first1=Isolde |title=Jay Inslee's uphill battle |url=https://www.seattlebusinessmag.com/article/jay-inslees-uphill-battle |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |publisher=Seattle Business Magazine |date=June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Washington House of Representatives (1989\u20131993)==\n\n===Elections===\nInslee ran for the [[Washington House of Representatives]] in 1988 after incumbent Republican State Representative Jim Lewis left office.<ref>{{cite web |title=State of Washington, Members of the Legislature, 1989-2005 |url=http://govinfo.askcarlos.com/wastate/legislators1895-2005.pdf |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> His opponent, Lynn Carmichael, was the former mayor of [[Yakima, Washington|Yakima]] and considered the front-runner in the race. Inslee also struggled to balance his more progressive ideology with the conservative leanings of [[Central Washington]]. His campaign attempted to rectify this by emphasizing his rural upbringing and legal experience supporting local average people, farms and businesses. The [[Washington State Association for Justice|Washington State Trial Lawyers Association]] became Inslee's biggest contributor.<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Craig |title=Inslee's political career took off as Democrat in GOP territory |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/inslees-political-career-took-off-as-democrat-in-gop-territory/ |accessdate=January 7, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=August 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen presented with a potential state budget surplus, Inslee called for a tax cut for the middle class, which Carmichael called irresponsible. Inslee claimed Carmichael had supported a [[sales tax]], which she denied. Inslee was an energetic and active campaigner, benefiting from [[Political campaign|retail politics]].<ref name=\"Early Campaigns\" />\n\nIn the blanket primary, Carmichael ranked first with 43% and Inslee ranked second with 40%. Republican Glen Blomgren ranked third with 17%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=533647 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 - Blanket Primary Race - Sep 20, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, Inslee defeated Carmichael 52%-48%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=407097 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 Race - Nov 08, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> In 1990, Inslee was reelected with 62% of the vote against Republican Ted Mellotte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=325303 |title=WA State House District 14 Seat 2 Race - Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn the Washington state legislature, Inslee pursued a bill to provide initial funding to build five branch campuses of the [[Washington State University]] system. Although the bill failed, his tenacity made an impression on House Speaker Joe King, who said: \"He's not afraid to incur the wrath of the speaker or the caucus.\"<ref>Yakima Herald-Republic, June 11, 1989.</ref> Inslee also focused on preventing [[Doping in sport|steroid usage]] among high school athletes and pushed for a bill requiring all drivers to carry [[vehicle insurance|auto insurance]].<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref> In 1991, he voted for a bill that required the state to devise a cost-effective energy strategy and state agencies and school districts to pursue and maintain energy-efficient operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=HB 1022 - 1991-92 |url=https://app.leg.wa.gov/billsummary?BillNumber=1022&Year=1991 |publisher=[[Washington State Legislature]] |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nInslee served on the Higher Education and Housing Committees.<ref>{{cite news |title=Millions for Migrant Housing Gets Nod |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oaJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G48DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6070,4754598&dq=jay+inslee&hl=en |accessdate=14 January 2020 |work=news.google.com |publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record |date=February 15, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ammons |first1=Dave |title=House Sets Up Showdown on Branch Campuses |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4YxfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9i8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=3090,5038870&dq=jay+inslee&hl=en |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=Lewiston Morning Tribune |date=May 31, 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Congress (1993\u20131995)==\n===Elections===\n;1992\n[[File:Jay Inslee, official 103rd Congress photo.png|thumb|160px|Inslee during the [[103rd United States Congress|103rd Congress]]]]\nIn 1992, six-term incumbent U.S. Representative [[Sid Morrison]] chose not to run for reelection representing {{ushr|Washington|4}}, instead mounting a campaign for governor. Morrison was a popular [[centre-right politics|moderate Republican]] incumbent who was considered successful and well-liked in the Democratic-controlled Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schaefer |first1=David |title=Primary Focus: Governor -- Morrison Takes High Road -- Congressman Hopes It Leads All The Way To State Capital |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19920827&slug=1509537 |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=August 27, 1992}}</ref> Despite initially declining to run, Inslee launched a campaign for the open Congressional seat, based in the central-eastern part of the state. His home area of the district, anchored by Yakima, is relatively rural and agriculture-based, while the southeastern part is more focused on research and nuclear waste disposal, anchored by the [[Tri-Cities, Washington|Tri-Cities]]. Inslee defeated a favored state senator to win the Democratic primary by 1%. Despite the district's conservative lean, Inslee won the general election in an extremely close race.<ref name=\"Political Career\">{{cite news |last1=Gutman |first1=David |title=Jay Inslee's Political Career: From small-town, part-time prosecutor to presidential candidate |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/jay-inslees-political-career-from-part-time-small-town-prosecutor-to-presidential-candidate/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weigel |first1=David |last2=Janes |first2=Chelsea |last3=Wagner |first3=John |title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee joins 2020 Democratic presidential field |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/washington-gov-jay-inslee-joins-2020-democratic-presidential-field/2019/03/01/d44e2366-0e9b-11e9-84fc-d58c33d6c8c7_story.html?noredirect=on |accessdate=29 August 2019 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n;1994\nHe lost his bid for reelection in the [[Republican Revolution]] of 1994 in a rematch against his 1992 opponent, [[Doc Hastings]]. Inslee attributed his 1994 defeat in large part to his vote for the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Postman, Sorrano|first=David, Barbara|title=Former Rep. Jay Inslee Joins Governor's Race|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951129&slug=2155065|accessdate=June 30, 2011|newspaper=Seattle Times|date=November 29, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn Congress, Inslee passed the Yakima River Enhancement Act, a bill long held up in Congress, by brokering a breakthrough with irrigators and wildlife advocates. He also helped to open Japanese markets to American apples and to fund and oversee the nation's biggest nuclear waste site at the [[Hanford Site|Hanford Nuclear Reservation]] near [[Richland, Washington]].<ref name=\"STimes1994\">[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960903&slug=2347250 Inslee Sticks To Campaign Game Plan -- Message Attempts To Boost His Profile], September 3, 1996.</ref><ref name=\"HR 1690\">{{USBill|103|HR|1690|pipe=H.R.1690: To authorize certain elements of the Yakima River Basin Water Enhancement Project, and for other purposes}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GVdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EI8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6322,438162&dq=jay+inslee+committee&hl=en|title=Ellensburg Daily Record - Google News Archive Search|work=google.com}}</ref>\n\n==Inter-congressional years (1995\u20131999)==\nInslee moved to [[Bainbridge Island]], a suburb of [[Seattle]], and briefly resumed the practice of law.<ref name=\"Political Career\"></ref>\n\n===1996 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|1996 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nHe ran for [[governor of Washington]] in [[Washington gubernatorial election, 1996|1996]] and lost in the [[blanket primary]]. Democratic [[King County Executive]] and former State Representative [[Gary Locke]] ranked first with 24% of the vote. Democratic [[Mayor of Seattle]] [[Norm Rice]] ranked second with 18%, but didn't qualify for the general election. Republican State Senator [[Ellen Craswell]] ranked third with 15%, and became the Republican candidate in the general election. Republican State Senator and Senate Majority Leader [[Dale Foreman]] ranked fourth with 13%. Inslee ranked fifth with 10%. No other candidate on the ballot received double digits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=18378 |title=WA Governor - All Party Primary Race - Sep 17, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Clinton administration===\nAfter Inslee's failed 1996 bid for [[governor of Washington]], [[President of the United States]] [[Bill Clinton]] appointed him regional director for the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Brian M. |title=Inslee-Clinton fundraiser almost sold out, boasts excited campaign |url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/politicsnorthwest/2012/09/06/inslee-clinton-fundraiser-almost-sold-out-boasts-excited-campaign/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Congress (1999\u20132012)==\n\n===Elections===\nInslee ran again for Congress in 1998, this time in the 1st congressional district against two-term incumbent [[Rick White (politician)|Rick White]]. His campaign attracted national attention when he became the first Democratic candidate to air television ads attacking his opponent and the Republican congressional leadership for the [[Lewinsky scandal]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaji |first1=Mina |last2=Szabo |first2=Christine |title=Jay Inslee: Everything you need to know about the former 2020 presidential candidate |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/jay-inslee/story?id=61305329 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=August 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"lewinskiad\">{{cite news |last1=Bolz |first1=Dan |title=Candidates Are Held Hostage by Scandal |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/campaign101198.htm |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=October 11, 1998}}</ref> Inslee won with 49.8% of the vote to White's 44.1%; he had an unintentional assist in his successful return by the conservative third-party candidacy of Bruce Craswell, husband of 1996 GOP gubernatorial nominee [[Ellen Craswell]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Christie |first1=Tim |title=ELECTION '98: White, Inslee see different reasons for result |url=https://products.kitsapsun.com/archive/1998/11-05/0086_election__98__white__inslee_see_d.html |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |publisher=Kitsap Sun |date=November 5, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Democrat Inslee bests incumbent White for Washington House seat |url=https://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/03/election/house/washington.cd1/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=November 4, 1998}}</ref>\n\nInslee was reelected six times. In 2000, he defeated [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]] Minority Leader Dan McDonald in 2000 with 54.6% of the vote. In 2002, Inslee defeated former state representative Joe Marine with 55.6% of the vote after the district was made more Democratic by redistricting. He never faced another contest that close, and was reelected three more times with over 60% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |title=The 2000 Campaign: Washington State;Primary Vote Bolsters House Democrat G.O.P. Saw As Vulnerable |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/02/us/2000-campaign-washington-state-primary-vote-bolsters-house-democrat-gop-saw.html |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=October 2, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"Inslee Results\">{{cite news |title=Inslee challengers look to curb spending |url=https://www.bainbridgereview.com/news/inslee-challengers-look-to-curb-spending/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=Bainbridge Island Review |date=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, after [[Gary Locke]] announced he would not seek a third term as Washington's governor, Inslee briefly flirted with a gubernatorial bid before deciding to remain in Congress.<ref name=\"inslee4gov\">[http://www.seattlepi.com/local/138758_governor09.html Inslee Won't Run For Governor], Joel Connelly, Seattle Post Intelligencer, September 8, 2003.</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009-10 campaign cycle, Inslee raised $1,140,025. In data compiled for the period 2005 to 2007 and excluding individual contributions of less than $200, 64 percent of Inslee's donations were from outside the state of Washington and 86 percent came from outside his district (compared to 79 percent for the average House member). 43 percent of Inslee's donations came from Washington, D.C., Virginia and Maryland. The largest interests funding Inslee's campaign were pharmaceutical and health-related companies, lawyers and law firms, and high-tech companies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Campaign Funding Sources|url=http://maplight.org/us-congress/legislator/297-jay-inslee|work=Inslee Contributions Illuminated|publisher=maplight.org|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Inslee Results\"/>\n\nIn 2010 he won by a 15-point margin, with 57.67% of the votes cast in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=Congressional District 1|url=http://vote.wa.gov/Elections/WEI/Results.aspx?ElectionID=37&JurisdictionTypeID=3&JurisdictionID=103&ViewMode=Results|work=2010 Election Results|publisher=Washington Secretary of State|accessdate=June 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321001943/http://vote.wa.gov/Elections/WEI/Results.aspx?ElectionID=37&JurisdictionTypeID=3&JurisdictionID=103&ViewMode=Results|archivedate=March 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Inslees and the Dalai Lama.jpg|thumb|Jay Inslee and his wife Trudi Inslee met with the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] in 2008.]]\nAs a member of the centrist [[New Democrat Coalition]], Inslee accumulated expertise on high-tech issues and vocally supported policies combating climate change.<ref name=\"STTech\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/techtracks/archives/2007/03/inslee_bill_would_push_fcc_on_white_space_decision.html|title=The Seattle Times: Tech Tracks|work=nwsource.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118135626/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/techtracks/archives/2007/03/inslee_bill_would_push_fcc_on_white_space_decision.html|archivedate=November 18, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"NDC\">{{cite news |title=Jay Inslee, with Climate Change Agenda, Running for President |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/03/01/jay-inslee-climate-change-democrat-president/ |accessdate=14 January 2020 |publisher=The Mercury News |date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nInslee was awarded a \"Friend of the National Parks\" award by the [[National Parks Conservation Association]] (NPCA) in 2001 for his support of legislation protecting the integrity and quality of the [[National Park System]].<ref name=\"NPCAfriend\">[http://www.npca.org/media_center/press_releases/2001/page-27598936.html Friend of the National Parks Award Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121111738/http://www.npca.org/media_center/press_releases/2001/page-27598936.html |date=November 21, 2008 }}, [[National Parks Conservation Association]], February 15, 2001</ref>\n\nInslee was \"one of Congress's most ardent advocates of strong action to combat global warming,\" according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=At House E.P.A. Hearing, Both Sides Claim Science |last=Broder |first=John M. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/science/earth/09climate.html |date=March 9, 2011 |page=17 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> He was the first public figure to propose an Apollo-like energy program, in an opinion editorial in the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' on December 19, 2002 and a series of similar pieces in other publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/opinion/100516_inslee19.shtml|title=New Apollo Project can help us unplug our need for oil|work=seattlepi.com}}</ref> Inslee co-authored ''[[Apollo's Fire (book)|Apollo's Fire: Igniting America's Clean Energy Economy]]'', in which he argues that through improved federal policies the United States can wean itself off foreign oil and [[fossil fuel]], create millions of [[green-collar]] jobs, and stop [[global warming]]. He has been a prominent supporter of the Apollo Alliance.<ref name=\"ApolloAlliance\">[http://www.apolloalliance.org/resources_100mpg.php Inslee articles at the Apollo Alliance web page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126233311/http://www.apolloalliance.org/resources_100mpg.php |date=November 26, 2008 }}</ref> Inslee strongly believes the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] should remain authorized to regulate [[greenhouse gas]] emissions. In a 2011 House hearing on the [[Energy Tax Prevention Act]], he said Republicans have \"an allergy to science and scientists\" during a discussion of whether the [[regulation of greenhouse gases under the Clean Air Act]] should remain in place following a controversial court finding on the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wing|first=Nick|title=Jay Inslee: Republicans Suffer From 'Allergy To Science And Scientists'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/09/jay-inslee-gop-allergy-science_n_833404.html|work=Huffpost Politics|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 1, 2011|date=March 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nInslee was an outspoken critic of the [[George W. Bush]] administration's [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. On July 31, 2007, he introduced legislation calling for an inquiry to determine whether then [[United States Attorney General]] [[Alberto Gonzales]] should be impeached. Gonzales eventually resigned.<ref name=\"LATimes20070801A\">[[Associated Press]], [https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/politics/la-na-impeach1aug01,1,130274.story?coll=la-news-politics-national&track=crosspromo ''Bill calls for Gonzales impeachment inquiry''], [[Los Angeles Times]], August 1, 2007</ref>\n\nStill an avid basketball player and fan, Inslee identified as a member of \"Hoopaholics\", a charity group dedicated to \"treatment of old guys addicted to basketball and who can no longer jump\", as Inslee has often joked.<ref name=\"hoopaholics\">[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/highschoolsports/2003867146_flashback04.html \"Flashback | Political football now Inslee's game], Seattle Times, September 4, 2007.</ref> In October 2009, he played basketball at the White House in a series of games featuring members of Congress on one team and members of the administration, including President Obama, on the other.<ref>{{cite news|last=Daly |first=Matthew |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2010027342_apusobamabasketballcongress.html |title=Local News &#124; Lawmakers play hoops with Obama at White House &#124; Seattle Times Newspaper |publisher=Seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=October 8, 2009 |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nInslee voted for the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], the federal health care law.<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 165 |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll165.xml |publisher=[[Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|Clerk of the US House of Representatives]] |date=March 21, 2010 |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Inslee voted in favor of authorizing the use of U.S. armed forces in the [[2011 Libyan civil war]] and against limiting the use of funds to support [[NATO]]'s [[2011 military intervention in Libya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congress Votes on Libya|url=http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400193_jay_inslee|work=Inslee Supports Adventure in Libya|publisher=OpenCongress.org|accessdate=July 1, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701094839/http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400193_Jay_Inslee|archivedate=July 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nInslee was once touted as a candidate for [[United States Secretary of the Interior]] and for [[United States Secretary of Energy]] during the [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"interiorapt\">[http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/politicsnorthwest/2008/10/31/inslee_for_interior_secretary.html Inslee For Interior Secretary?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126133645/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/politicsnorthwest/2008/10/31/inslee_for_interior_secretary.html|date=January 26, 2009}} Seattle Times, October 31, 2008</ref><ref name=\"DOEapt\">[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/energywire/2008/11/obamas_energy_department.html Obama's Energy Department] Newsweek/Washington Post EnergyWire, Steve Mufson, November 6, 2008</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2012, Inslee left Congress to focus on his campaign for governor of Washington.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Song |first1=Kyung M. |title=Inslee leaving U.S. House but still eligible for pension |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/inslee-leaving-us-house-but-still-eligible-for-pension/ |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=March 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Friends of Animals Caucus\n* Congressional Internet Caucus\n* House Medicare and Medicaid Fairness Caucus\n* House Oceans Caucus\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]\n* Congressional Arts Caucus\n* Sustainable Energy and Environment Coalition\n\n==Governor of Washington (2013\u2013present)==\n\n===2012 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|2012 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nOn June 27, 2011, Inslee announced his candidacy for governor of Washington.<ref name=\"insleeannounces\">[http://kuow.org/program.php?id=23805 Inslee Announces Run For Governor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015020823/http://kuow.org/program.php?id=23805 |date=October 15, 2011 }}, Liz Jones, KUOW, June 28, 2011.</ref> His campaign focused on job creation, outlining dozens of proposals to increase job growth in clean energy, the aerospace industry, and biotechnology. He also supported a ballot measure to legalize gay marriage, which passed, and opposed tax increases.<ref name=\"won'tconcede\">[http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019621861_elexgovernor07m.html Inslee takes strong lead, but McKenna won't concede], Jim Brunner, Seattle Times, November 7, 2012.</ref> He won election with 51% of the vote, a three-point margin over his Republican opponent, [[Rob McKenna]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=WA STATE Gubernatorial results|url=http://sos.wa.gov|publisher=WA STATE SEC OF STATE|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130223191448/http://sos.wa.gov/|archivedate=February 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2016 gubernatorial election===\n{{main|2016 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nIn December 2015, Inslee announced on Washington's public affairs TV channel [[TVW (Washington)|TVW]] that he would run for a second term as governor. He emphasized increased spending on transportation and education as his primary first-term accomplishment, though he had struggled to work with the Republican-controlled [[Majority Coalition Caucus]] in the State Senate.<ref name=\"NWNews\">{{cite news |last1=Jenkins |first1=Austin |title=Inslee Vs. Bryant: A Preview Of The 2016 Washington Gubernatorial Face-Off |url=https://www.nwnewsnetwork.org/post/inslee-vs-bryant-preview-2016-washington-gubernatorial-face |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=NW News Network |date=December 9, 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the general election Inslee faced former Port of Seattle Commissioner [[Bill Bryant (politician)|Bill Bryant]]. The primary issues of the campaign were [[climate change]], job creation, [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum wage]], and [[Capital gains tax|capital gains taxes]]. Inslee far outraised Bryant,<ref name=\"Win Second\"/><ref name=\"NWNews\"/><ref name=\"King5\"/> and was reelected in November with 54% of the vote.<ref name=\"Win Second\">{{cite news |last1=Wissel |first1=Paula |title=Gov. Jay Inslee Defeats Bill Bryant To Win Second Term |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/washington-governor-jay-inslee-bill-bryant/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KNKX News |date=November 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inslee defeats Bryant in Wash. Governor race |url=https://www.kxly.com/inslee-defeats-bryant-in-wash-governor-race/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KXLY |date=November 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"King5\">{{cite news |title=Wash. Governor Inslee wins second term |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/wash-governor-inslee-wins-second-term/281-348472289 |accessdate=January 5, 2019 |publisher=KING5 |date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2020 gubernatorial election===\n{{main|2020 Washington gubernatorial election}}\nOn March 1, 2019, Inslee announced he would run for president, but kept open the possibility of running for a third term if his presidential campaign failed. Several potential Democratic gubernatorial candidates, including state Attorney General [[Bob Ferguson (politician)|Bob Ferguson]], Commissioner of Public Lands [[Hilary Franz]], and King County Executive [[Dow Constantine]], were all waiting to announce campaigns until Inslee made his decision.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oxley |first1=Dyer |title=What will they do now that Jay Inslee is running for governor again? |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1488696/constantine-ferguson-franz-governor-inslee/? |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=MYNorthwest |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> As Inslee's presidential campaign failed to gain traction during the summer of 2019, he was pressured to drop out and make his gubernatorial plans clear to the other potential candidates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kruse |first1=Brandi |title=It\u2019s decision time for Washington Governor Jay Inslee |url=https://q13fox.com/2019/08/20/its-decision-time-for-washington-governor-jay-inslee/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=Q13 FOX |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> On August 21, 2019, Inslee dropped out of the presidential campaign and announced the next day he would run for reelection as governor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gottlieb |first1=Paul |title=If Jay Inslee leaves governor job, AG Bob Ferguson may run |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/northwest/if-jay-inslee-leaves-governor-job-ag-bob-ferguson-may-run/ |accessdate=January 14, 2019 |publisher=Everett Herald |date=May 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"USA 3rd\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Kip |title=Gov. Jay Inslee announces re-election bid; AG Bob Ferguson also will seek re-election |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2019/aug/22/gov-jay-inslee-announces-re-election-bid-ag-bob-fe/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=The Spokesman-Review |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2020, Inslee's major opponents in the election are State Senator [[Phil Fortunato]]; [[Republic, Washington]] police chief Loren Culp; and former [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] mayor Joshua Freed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennings |first1=Nicole |title=Gubernatorial candidate Joshua Freed walks a middle line for homelessness |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1509750/dori-joshua-freed/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KIRO Radio |date=September 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Former Bothell mayor announces gubernatorial run |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/former-bothell-mayor-announces-gubernatorial-run/281-5c792fb2-a48a-487d-afe2-d4aff379034c |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KING5 |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== First term: 2013\u20132017 ===\nDuring the 2013 session, the [[Washington State Legislature|legislature]] failed to create a fiscal budget plan during the initial session, and Inslee was forced to call two special sessions to provide time for a budget to be created. The Republican-controlled [[Washington State Senate|Senate]] and Democratic-controlled [[Washington State House of Representatives|House]] each passed its own budget and could not agree on one.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee calls second special session|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/06/washington_gov_jay_inslee_call_1.html|newspaper=Oregon Live|date=June 11, 2013}}</ref> Finally, in June 2013, Inslee signed a $33.6 billion budget to which both houses had agreed as a compromise. The budget increased funding for education by $1 billion. It also adjusted [[property tax|property taxes]] and [[tax break|tax breaks]] in order to increase state revenue by $1 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Mike |title=A look inside Washington state's $33.6 billion budget plan |url=https://komonews.com/news/local/a-look-inside-washington-states-336-billion-budget-plan-11-20-2015 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=KOMO News |date=June 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2013, Inslee signed an additional [[estate tax]] into law. The tax had bipartisan support, and passed the Senate, 30\u201319.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee signs estate tax fix into law|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/06/washington_gov_jay_inslee_sign.html|newspaper=Oregon Live|date=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jay Inslee Speech (8724201105).jpg|thumb|left|Inslee giving a speech regarding [[Boeing]] in May 2013]]\nIn December 2013, Inslee was elected to serve as finance chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Burns|first=Alexander|title=DGA appoints leaders for 2014|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/dga-appoints-leaders-for-2014-100877.html?hp=f1|publisher=Politico|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, Inslee gave a speech commending machinists who voted to renew [[Boeing]]'s contract with Seattle area union employees, allowing the company to build its [[Boeing 777X|Boeing 777x]] aircraft [[Boeing Everett Factory|in Everett]]. He said the contract would bring Washington to a new industrial plateau and be a turning point for Washington jobs:\n\n<blockquote>These jobs are in the thousands and it is not only on the 777X, the first model of the 777X, but all the subsequent derivative models as well.</blockquote>\n\nThe plan was to prevent Boeing from building part of the aircraft in Washington and part of it elsewhere, as they did with the [[Boeing 787]], which was partially constructed in [[South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Hana|title=Governor Inslee says Boeing deal could open new industrial plateau|url=http://q13fox.com/2014/01/04/governor-inslee-says-boeing-deal-could-open-new-industrial-plateau/#axzz2pVAPMUv4|newspaper=Q13 Fox|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Boeing pact with Machinists union called turning point for labor|url=http://triblive.com/business/headlines/5360816-74/boeing-union-state#axzz2pVAQFg9d|newspaper=TribLive|date=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2014, Inslee announced a [[Moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on [[Capital punishment in Washington state|executions in Washington]]:\n\n<blockquote>There have been too many doubts raised about capital punishment, there are too many flaws in this system today. There is too much at stake to accept an imperfect system.</blockquote>\n\nInslee cited the high cost of pursuing the death penalty, the randomness with which it is sought, and the lack of evidence that it is a deterrent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inslee halts executions in state while he is governor|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2022883256_deathpenaltyinsleexml.html|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Washington state to suspend death penalty by governor's moratorium|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/11/washington-state-death-penalty-governor-inslee-suspends|newspaper=The Guardian|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Second term: 2017\u2013present ===\nInslee began his second term in January 2017, proposing full funding of state education (in compliance with the [[McCleary decision]]) and addressing mental health needs while also raising worker pay.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Sullivan |first=Joseph |date=January 9, 2017 |title=State lawmakers face tough fight over education funding as legislative session opens |page=B1 |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/state-lawmakers-face-tough-fight-over-education-funding-as-legislative-session-opens/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> After newly inaugurated President [[Donald Trump]] signed an [[Executive Order 13769|executive order on January 27 banning people from seven Muslim-majority countries from entering the United States]], Inslee and Attorney General [[Bob Ferguson (politician)|Bob Ferguson]] announced their intention to sue Trump, alleging his order was unconstitutional. The civil action, ''[[Washington v. Trump]]'', was filed on January 30 and on February 3 successfully earned a [[temporary restraining order]] to forbid federal enforcement of some of the ban's provisions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Burns |first=Alexander |date=January 30, 2017 |title=Legal Challenges Mount Against Trump's Travel Ban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/30/us/legal-challenges-mount-against-trumps-travel-ban.html?_r=0 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Burns |first=Alexander |date=February 4, 2017 |title=How Washington State Upended Trump's Travel Ban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/trump-travel-ban-washington-seattle-ferguson.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> An appeal and request to stay filed by the federal government was subsequently denied by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]. Inslee and Ferguson declared victory over Trump on February 16, after his administration announced it would revise the travel ban to comply with the court decisions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dolan |first1=Maura |last2=Kaleem |first2=Jaweed |date=February 16, 2017 |title=Trump says he will issue a new order after a 'very bad decision' blocked his initial travel ban |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-travel-executive-order-20170216-story.html |work=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Inslee garnered national media attention during the lawsuit.<ref name=\"seattletimes_inslees_profile\">{{cite news |last=Brunner |first=Jim |date=February 21, 2017 |title=Jay Inslee for president? Governor's profile is on the rise |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/inslees-profile-lifted-with-states-legal-victories-on-immigration/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2017 legislative session, the [[Washington State Legislature]] failed to pass a state operating budget by the end of its regular session on April 25, so Inslee called for a 30-day special session. The legislature again failed to pass a budget during that session, forcing Inslee to call a third one, beginning June 22. As the state's fiscal year ends on June 30, a [[Government shutdowns in the United States|partial government shutdown]] was feared.<ref>{{cite news |last1=La Corte |first1=Rachel |title=No end in sight as Washington lawmakers edge toward a third special session |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/may/23/washington-legislatures-first-special-session-ends/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> Conflict over resource allocation between [[Rural areas in the United States|rural areas]] and [[United States urban area|urban areas]] was a major reason for the impasse. The [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]] passed a budget on June 30 and Inslee signed it into law shortly after 11 pm. Its specifics were still being released several hours after it was enacted. Lawmakers critiqued the haste with which the budget was considered and passed, having received the 616-page document only that day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Camden |first1=Jim |title=Legislature passes $43.7 billion budget, and taxes to pay for it; Inslee signs before midnight |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/jun/30/437-billion-washington-budget-begins-push-through-/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=Spokesman-Review |date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> By the end of the third session on July 20, the legislature had still failed to pass a [[Capital budgeting|capital budget]] concerning long-term goals and improvements.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brand |first1=Natalie |last2=Graf |first2=Heather |title=Washington lawmakers adjourn with no capital budget |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/politics/washington-lawmakers-adjourn-with-no-capital-budget/281-458374474 |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=King5 |date=July 20, 2017}}</ref> This was the third time during Inslee's tenure the state's budget was passed in the last week of the legislative session.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Melissa |title=Threat of shutdown looms as Legislature heads into triple overtime over budget |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article157434149.html |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |agency=The News Tribune |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017 Inslee awarded $6.4 million in grant funding for apprenticeships and career connections to 29,000 youth in 11 communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/wagovernor/inslee-awards-6-4-129c4de96df3|title=Inslee awards $6 million to create apprenticeship and career connections for 29,000 youth in 11 communities|date=December 8, 2017|website=Medium}}</ref> He called this initiative [https://careerconnectwa.org/ Career Connect Washington]. It includes a Task Force and several prominent stakeholder groups including [[Alaska Airlines]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Boeing]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Kaiser Permanente]]. Career Connect Washington has established new apprenticeship opportunities, including the [https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/education/article143777889.html Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Committee]'s registered Youth Apprenticeship program for high school students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtb.wa.gov/careerconnectwa.asp|title=Career Connected Washington Task Force|website=Workforce Training & Education Board}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/washington-voters-dont-think-schools-prepare-kids-for-careers-the-state-is-trying-to-change-that/|title=Washington voters don't think schools prepare kids for careers. The state is trying to change that.|date=October 31, 2018|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=November 16, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nInslee served as chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2018|2018 election cycle]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mycolumbiabasin.com/2017/12/04/washington-governor-elected-next-dga-chair/|title=Washington governor elected next DGA chair|date=December 4, 2017|work=My Columbia Basin|access-date=December 5, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> in which Democrats gained seven net governorships nationwide.<ref name=\"theatlantic_201901\">{{cite news |last1=Dovere |first1=Edward-Isaac |title=Jay Inslee Is Betting He Can Win the Presidency on Climate Change |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/01/washington-governor-jay-inslee-running-president/579217/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=The Atlantic |date=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Inslee announced new legislation aimed at reducing the state's carbon emissions over approximately two decades. It would effectively require Washington utilities to end the use of fossil fuels by mid-century, making Washington \"adopt a clean fuel standard\", \"promote electric and low-emission vehicles\", and \"provide incentives to renovate existing buildings to reduce\" emissions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Reid |title=Washington governor plans major climate initiatives |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/420611-washington-governor-plans-major-climate-initiatives |website=The Hill |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Inslee said he would provide an expedited process for approximately 3,500 people convicted of small-time cannabis possession to apply for and receive pardons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/legal-pot/washington-gov-inslee-pardon-thousands-convicted-marijuana-possession-n954981|title=Washington Gov. Inslee to pardon thousands convicted of marijuana possession|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March and April 2020, Inslee ordered significant social distancing measures statewide, including banning large events, a stay-at-home order, and the closing of all schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/inslee-extends-stay-home-stay-healthy-through-may-4|title=Inslee extends 'Stay Home, Stay Healthy' through May 4 {{!}} Governor Jay Inslee|website=www.governor.wa.gov|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{main|Jay Inslee 2020 presidential campaign}}\n[[File:Jay Inslee presidential announcement - March 1, 2019 - 01 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Inslee declaring his candidacy for president]]\n\nThroughout 2018, speculation rose that Inslee might run for [[President of the United States]] in [[2020 United States presidential election|the 2020 election]]. He garnered national attention because of ''[[Washington v. Trump]],'' a lawsuit challenging the [[Trump Administration|Trump Administration's]] [[Executive Order 13769|order to ban people from seven Muslim-majority countries from entering the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wang |first=Amy B. |date=February 5, 2017 |title=How Washington state became the epicenter of resistance to Trump's agenda |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/02/05/how-washington-state-became-the-epicenter-of-resistance-to-trumps-agenda/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"seattletimes_inslees_profile\"/> While Inslee was chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]], Democrats gained seven net governorships in [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|the 2018 gubernatorial elections]], further propelling him into the national spotlight and fueling speculation that he would run.<ref name=\"theatlantic_201901\"/> Inslee cited [[climate change]] as his primary motivation for running, strongly criticizing the Trump Administration's policies.<ref name=\"Inslee-presidential-2020\">{{cite news|last=Brunner|first=Jim|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/gov-jay-inslees-new-pac-raises-112000-as-he-actively-considers-presidential-run/|title=Gov. Jay Inslee's new PAC raises $112,000 as he 'actively' considers presidential run|date=December 6, 2018|work=[[Seattle Times]]|access-date=December 7, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, reports surfaced that Inslee was beginning to form an [[exploratory committee]], the first step in a campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kroll |first1=Andy |title=Jay Inslee, the 'Climate Candidate,' Joins the 2020 Race |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/jay-inslee-2020-774051/ |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=January 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/01/washington-governor-jay-inslee-running-president/579217/|title=Jay Inslee Is Betting He Can Win the Presidency on Climate Change|last=Dovere|first=Edward-Isaac|date=January 2, 2019|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=January 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/jay-inslee-is-running-for-president-governor-of-washington/|title=Jay Inslee Is Running For President \u2014 You Know, the Governor of Washington|date=January 2, 2019|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=January 2, 2019}}</ref> Inslee was a [[dark horse|dark-horse]] candidate; initially, he was rarely included in [[Opinion polling for the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|polling for the primary]], was not well known outside Washington, and made few trips to early primary states such as Iowa and New Hampshire. But he pointed to former Presidents [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Bill Clinton]], calling them \"pretty much unknown governors of small states\" and adding, \"this is a wide-open field. No one has a lock on this. No one has a total crystal ball as to what the nation wants.\"<ref name=\"Inslee-presidential-2020\" />\n\nInslee announced his candidacy for president on March 1, 2019, saying he would focus on combating climate change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.cnn.com/en/article/h_938905d87233bde443acdaa78523780d|title=CNN - Breaking News, Latest News and Videos|website=m.cnn.com|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> His campaign requested a debate focused on climate change. The [[Democratic National Committee]] denied the request, but 53 of its voting members wrote an open letter protesting that decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/05/politics/jay-inslee-climate-change-cnntv/index.html|title=Inslee: DNC rejecting climate change debate is \"extremely disappointing\"|first=Kate|last=Sullivan|publisher=CNN|date=2019-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/53-voting-dnc-members-protest-rejection-jay-inslees-climate-change-debate-4274c1fc-eae4-4d88-9757-f62ad3200667.html|title=53 DNC members protest rejection of Jay Inslee's climate change debate|first=Orion|last=Rummier|publisher=Axios|date=2019-06-08|accessdate=2019-06-08}}</ref>\n\nFacing poor polling numbers and seeing no path to victory, Inslee announced the suspension of his campaign on ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' on August 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jay Inslee, governor who centered climate change in presidential race, drops out of the contest |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/08/22/jay-inslee-governor-who-centered-climate-change-presidential-race-drops-out-contest/ |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Inslee, exiting the presidential race, reflects on his campaign|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2019/8/21/20826258/jay-inslee-presidential-exit-interview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|accessdate=August 21, 2019|date=August 21, 2019|author=David Roberts}}</ref> The next day, he announced he would run for a third term as governor in [[2020 Washington gubernatorial election|the 2020 election]].<ref name=\"USA 3rd\">{{cite news |last1=Santucci |first1=Jeanine |title=Jay Inslee begins campaign for 3rd term as governor after dropping out of presidential race |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/22/jay-inslee-seek-3rd-washington-governor-term-after-ending-2020-bid/2087537001/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |publisher=USA Today |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Jay Inslee}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date || Position || Status || Opponent || Result || Vote share || Opponent vote share\n|-\n| 1988 || WA Representative || Open seat || || Elected || ||\n|-\n| 1990 || WA Representative || Incumbent || || Re-elected || ||\n|-\n| 1992 || U.S. Representative || Open seat || [[Doc Hastings]] (R) || Elected || 51% 