{"title_page": "Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Klymaxx]]\n| cover      = Never Underestimate The Power Of A Woman cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1981\n| recorded   = 1981\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[SOLAR Records|SOLAR]]\n| producer   = Otis Stokes, Stephen Shockley\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Girls Will Be Girls (Klymaxx album)|Girls Will Be Girls]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{cite web|last=Wynn |first=Ron|url={{Allmusic|class=album |id=r11097/review |pure_url=yes}} |title=''Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman'' review |publisher=[[Allmusic]]|date= |accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman''''' is the debut album by R&B group [[Klymaxx]]. Released in 1981, it was produced by Otis Stokes and Stephen Shockley.  The title is taken from the slogan of ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"All Fired Up\"  (Stephen Shockley, Otis Stokes) \u2013 6:19\n#\"I Wish You Would (Tell Me Something Good)\"   (Fred, Shockley, Walton, Walton) \u2013 4:38\n#\"I Want to Love You Tonight\" \t(Lynn Malsby) \u2013 5:06\n#\"You're the Greatest\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:02\n#\"Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman\"  (Bernadette Cooper, Cheryl Cooley) \u2013 5:08\n#\"The Beat of My Heart (is for You)\"  (Marchbanks, Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 5:48\n#\"No Words\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:22\n#\"Can't Let Love Just Pass Me By\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:48\n\n==Personnel==\n* Cheryl Cooley \u2013 guitar, backing vocals \n* Bernadette Cooper \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals \n* Robbin Grider \u2013 synthesizers\n* [[Joyce Irby|Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals \n* Lynn Malsby \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals \n* Lorena Porter Shelby \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[The Sylvers|Patricia Sylvers]] \u2013 backing vocals \n* Judy Takeuchi \u2013 percussion\n* Ann Williams \u2013 guitar\n\n=== Production ===\n* Stephen Shockley \u2013 producer \n* Otis Stokes \u2013 producer\n* Dick Griffey \u2013 executive producer \n* Steve Hodge \u2013 recording engineer, mixing \n* Taavi Mote \u2013 recording engineer \n* Bob Brown \u2013 additional engineer\n* Sabrina Buchaner \u2013 additional engineer\n* Wally Traugott \u2013 mastering \n* Dina Andrews \u2013 A&R coordination\n* Henry Vizcarra \u2013 art direction\n* Jan Kovaleski \u2013 design  \n* Jay Pope \u2013 back cover photo, dust sleeve photography \n* Veronica Sim \u2013 photography\n; Studios\n* Recorded at Studio Masters (Los Angeles, California) and [[Larrabee Sound Studios]] (Hollywood, California).\n* Mixed at Larrabee Sound Studios\n* Mastered at [[Capitol Records]] (Hollywood, California).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[http://www.discogs.com/Klymaxx-Never-Underestimate-The-Power-Of-A-Woman/master/143578 Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman]'' at [[Discogs]]\n\n[[Category:1981 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Klymaxx albums]]\n[[Category:SOLAR Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Klymaxx]]\n| cover      = Never Underestimate The Power Of A Woman cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1981\n| recorded   = 1981\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[SOLAR Records|SOLAR]]\n| producer   = Otis Stokes, Stephen Shockley\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Girls Will Be Girls (Klymaxx album)|Girls Will Be Girls]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{cite web|last=Wynn |first=Ron|url={{Allmusic|class=album |id=r11097/review |pure_url=yes}} |title=''Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman'' review |publisher=[[Allmusic]]|date= |accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman''''' is the debut album by R&B group [[Klymaxx]]. Released in 1981, it was produced by Otis Stokes and Stephen Shockley.  The title is taken from the slogan of ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"All Fired Up\"  (Stephen Shockley, Otis Stokes) \u2013 6:19\n#\"I Wish You Would (Tell Me Something Good)\"   (Fred, Shockley, Walton, Walton) \u2013 4:38\n#\"I Want to Love You Tonight\" \t(Lynn Malsby) \u2013 5:06\n#\"You're the Greatest\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:02\n#\"Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman\"  (Bernadette Cooper, Cheryl Cooley) \u2013 5:08\n#\"The Beat of My Heart (is for You)\"  (Marchbanks, Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 5:48\n#\"No Words\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:22\n#\"Can't Let Love Just Pass Me By\"  (Shockley, Stokes) \u2013 4:48\n\n==Personnel==\n* Cheryl Cooley \u2013 guitar, backing vocals \n* Bernadette Cooper \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals \n* Robbin Grider \u2013 synthesizers\n* [[Joyce Irby|Joyce \"Fenderella\" Irby]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals \n* Lynn Malsby \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals \n* Lorena Porter Shelby \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[The Sylvers|Patricia Sylvers]] \u2013 backing vocals \n* Judy Takeuchi \u2013 percussion\n* Ann Williams \u2013 guitar\n\n=== Production ===\n* Stephen Shockley \u2013 producer \n* Otis Stokes \u2013 producer\n* Dick Griffey \u2013 executive producer \n* Steve Hodge \u2013 recording, mixing \n* Taavi Mote \u2013 recording\n* Bob Brown \u2013 additional engineer\n* Sabrina Buchaner \u2013 additional engineer\n* Wally Traugott \u2013 mastering \n* Dina Andrews \u2013 A&R coordination\n* Henry Vizcarra \u2013 art direction\n* Jan Kovaleski \u2013 design  \n* Jay Pope \u2013 back cover photo, dust sleeve photography \n* Veronica Sim \u2013 photography\n; Studios\n* Recorded at Studio Masters (Los Angeles, California) and [[Larrabee Sound Studios]] (Hollywood, California).\n* Mixed at Larrabee Sound Studios\n* Mastered at [[Capitol Records]] (New York City, New York).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[http://www.discogs.com/Klymaxx-Never-Underestimate-The-Power-Of-A-Woman/master/143578 Never Underestimate the Power of a Woman]'' at [[Discogs]]\n\n[[Category:1981 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Klymaxx albums]]\n[[Category:SOLAR Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Joshuadejohnson", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Never_Underestimate_the_Power_of_a_Woman"}
{"title_page": "Gary Locke", "text_new": "{{other people|Gary Locke}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{stack begin}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Gary Locke\n|native_name  = {{nobold|\u99f1\u5bb6\u8f1d}}\n|native_name_lang = zh-hant\n|image        = Gary Locke official portrait.jpg\n|office       = 10th [[United States Ambassador to China]]\n|president    = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = August 16, 2011\n|term_end     = March 1, 2014\n|predecessor  = [[Jon Huntsman Jr.]]\n|successor    = [[Max Baucus]]\n|office1      = 36th [[United States Secretary of Commerce]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Dennis Hightower]]<br />[[Rebecca Blank]] (acting)\n|term_start1  = March 26, 2009\n|term_end1    = August 1, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Carlos Gutierrez]]\n|successor1   = [[John Bryson]]\n|order2       = 21st [[List of governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]\n|lieutenant2  = [[Brad Owen]]\n|term_start2  = January 15, 1997\n|term_end2    = January 12, 2005\n|predecessor2 = [[Mike Lowry]]\n|successor2   = [[Christine Gregoire]]\n|office3      = 5th [[King County Executive]]\n|term_start3  = January 4, 1994\n|term_end3    = January 15, 1997\n|predecessor3 = [[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]]\n|successor3   = [[Ron Sims]]\n|state_house4 = Washington\n|district4    = 37th\n|term_start4  = January 10, 1983\n|term_end4    = January 3, 1994\n|predecessor4 = [[Peggy Maxie]]\n|successor4   = [[Vivian Caver]]\n|birth_name   = Gary Faye Locke\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1950|1|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Mona Lee|1994|2015|reason=div.}}\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Boston University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|showflag = j\n|t        = \u99f1\u5bb6\u8f1d\n|s        = \u9a86\u5bb6\u8f89\n|p        = Lu\u00f2 Ji\u0101hu\u012b\n|j        = Lok<sup>3</sup> Gaa<sup>1</sup> fai<sup>1</sup>\n|y        = Lok G\u0101f\u0101i\n}}\n{{stack end}}\n\n'''Gary Faye Locke''' (born January 21, 1950) is an American politician and diplomat who served as the 10th [[United States Ambassador to China|United States ambassador to China]] (2011\u201314). He was previously the [[List of Governors of Washington|21st governor of Washington]] (1997\u20132005) and served in the [[Obama administration]] as [[United States Secretary of Commerce]] (2009\u201311).\nLocke is the first [[Governor (United States)|governor]] in the [[continental United States]] of [[Asian Americans|East Asian descent]] and the only [[Chinese Americans|Chinese American]] ever to have served as a governor of any state. He was also the first Chinese American to serve as the U.S. ambassador to China.<ref name=\"TimeBio\">{{cite news|title=Commerce Secretary: Gary Locke|author=Gilbert Cruz|date=February 25, 2009|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1881587,00.html|accessdate=March 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGary Locke was born on January 21, 1950, in Seattle, [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and spent his early years living in the [[Yesler Terrace, Seattle|Yesler Terrace]] public [[public housing|housing project]]. A third-generation Chinese American with paternal ancestry from Jilong village,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2011/11/gary-locke-visits-his-family%E2%80%99s-ancestral-village-in-china-with-his-sister-rita/|title=Gary Locke visits his family's ancestral village in China with his sister Rita|date=12 November 2011|publisher=Northwest Asian Weekly}}</ref> [[Taishan, Guangdong|Taishan]], [[Guangdong]], [[China]], Locke is the second of five children of James Locke, who served as a [[Staff sergeant#United States|staff sergeant]] in the [[5th Armored Division (United States)|U.S. Fifth Armored Division]] during [[World War&nbsp;II]]. His wife, Julie, is from [[Hong Kong]],<ref>[http://www.thenewstribune.com/2011/01/16/1504584/jimmy-locke-father-of-former-gov.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111132348/http://www.thenewstribune.com/2011/01/16/1504584/jimmy-locke-father-of-former-gov.html |date=January 11, 2012 }}</ref> which at that time was a [[British Crown Colony]]/[[British Hong Kong]]. His paternal grandfather left China in the 1890s and moved to the United States, where he worked as a [[houseboy]] in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]], Washington, in exchange for [[English language|English]] lessons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Commerce Secretary Gary Locke on Asian-American and Pacific Islander Month 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z-f3mIn-HTI|date=April 30, 2010|publisher=Commerce News|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Gary Locke did not learn how to speak English until he was five years old and entered kindergarten.<ref name=\"english\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Remarks-by-President-Obama-and-Commerce-Secretary-Nominee-Gary-Locke/|title=Remarks by President Obama and Commerce Secretary Nominee Gary Locke|date=February 25, 2009|publisher=Whitehouse.gov|accessdate=July 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLocke graduated with honors from Seattle's [[Franklin High School (Seattle)|Franklin High School]] in 1968. He achieved [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] rank and received the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] from the [[Scouting in Washington (state)|Boy Scouts of America]].<ref name=\"english\"/><ref name=\"HistoryLinkBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?displaypage=output.cfm&file_id=7830| title=Locke, Gary Faye (b. 1950)|publisher=[[HistoryLink]]|author=Frank Chesley|date= June 29, 2006|accessdate=March 25, 2009}}</ref> Through a combination of part-time jobs, financial aid, and scholarships, Locke attended [[Yale University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] in 1972.<ref name=AsianBio>{{cite web|accessdate=November 9, 2008|url=http://www.asianamerican.net/bios/Locke-Gary.html|title=Biography of Governor Gary Locke|website=Who's Who of Asian Americans}}</ref> He later received his [[Juris Doctor|juris doctor]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1975.\n\n==Career==\n===Washington representative===\nIn 1982, Locke was elected to Washington state's South Seattle district in the [[Washington House of Representatives]], where he served as the chair of the Appropriations Committee. Eleven years later, in 1993, Locke was elected as [[King County, Washington|King County]]'s executive, defeating incumbent [[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]].\n\n===Governor===\n[[File:Gary Locke.jpg|thumb|left|Locke as Governor of Washington]]\nIn 1996, Locke won the [[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|Democratic primary and general election for governor of Washington]], becoming the first Chinese American governor in United States history. His political committee was fined $2,500 by regulators in 1997 after admitting to state campaign finance law violations during his successful campaign.<ref name=\"Sidoti\">{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090225/ap_on_go_pr_wh/obama_commerce |title=Obama selected Locke to run Commerce Department |agency=Associated Press |work=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Liz |last=Sidoti |date=February 25, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228162329/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090225/ap_on_go_pr_wh/obama_commerce |archivedate=February 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nLocke faced criticism from fellow Democrats for embracing the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]'s \"no-new-taxes\" approach to dealing with Washington's budget woes during and after the 2001 economic turmoil. Among his spending-reduction proposals were laying off thousands of state employees; reducing health coverage; freezing most state employees' pay; and cutting funding for nursing homes and programs for the [[developmentally disabled]]. In his final budget, Locke suspended two voter-passed school initiatives and cut state education funding. Supported by the state's political left, former [[Washington Supreme Court]] Justice [[Phil Talmadge]] announced his plans to challenge Locke in the 2004 Democratic primary, but Talmadge ended his campaign early for health reasons; Locke [[2000 Washington gubernatorial election|won re-election in 2000]].\n\nOn the national stage, Democrats saw Gary Locke as a possible vice-presidential choice. In 1997, Locke was a guest at that year's [[State of the Union address]].<ref>{{cite web|author = Clinton, Bill|title = Remarks By The President In State Of The Union Address|website = The White House|date = February 4, 1997|url = http://clinton2.nara.gov/WH/SOU97/|accessdate = February 24, 2009|quote = Gary Locke, the newly elected Governor of Washington State, is the first Chinese American governor in the history of our country. He's the proud son of two of the millions of Asian American immigrants who have strengthened America with their hard work, family values and good citizenship. He represents the future we can all achieve. Thank you, Governor, for being here. Please stand up.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716023357/http://clinton2.nara.gov/WH/SOU97/|archive-date = July 16, 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nLocke was chosen to give his party's response to [[George W. Bush]]'s [[2003 State of the Union Address]].<ref name=\"speaker\">{{cite press release|title = Democratic Leaders Announce Governor Gary Locke Will Deliver the Democratic Response to State of the Union Address|publisher = Congresswoman Nancy Pelosi|date = January 15, 2003|url = http://www.house.gov/pelosi/prGovGaryLocke011503.htm|accessdate = February 24, 2009|quote = Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle and House Democratic Leader Nancy Pelosi announced today that Governor Gary Locke of Washington state will deliver the Democratic response to President Bush\u2019s State of the Union address.|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090301105025/http://www.house.gov/pelosi/prGovGaryLocke011503.htm|archivedate = March 1, 2009|df = mdy-all}}</ref> In a surprise move, Locke announced in July 2003 that he would not seek a third term,<ref name=\"retire\">{{cite press release|title = Gov. Gary Locke Announces He Will Not Seek a Third Term|publisher = Washington State Office of the Governor|date = July 21, 2003|url = http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/press/press-view.asp?pressRelease=1403&newsType=1|accessdate =February 24, 2009|quote = }}</ref> saying, \"Despite my deep love of our state, I want to devote more time to my family.\"<ref name=\"retire\"/> [[Susan Paynter]], a columnist at the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'', suggested that racist slurs, insults, and threats that Locke and his family received, especially a large number which came after his rebuttal to George W. Bush's 2003 State of the Union address, may have played a role in Locke's decision to leave office after two terms.<ref name=PI_Paynter_20030726>{{cite news|url= http://www.seattlepi.com/paynter/132272_paynter25.html |accessdate=December 17, 2007|title= Threats to Locke's family are a factor in third-term decision|last= Paynter|first=Susan|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date= July 26, 2003}}</ref> The governor's office received hundreds of threatening letters and e-mails; others threatened to kill his children.<ref name=PI_Paynter_20030726/> His official portrait, painted by [[Michele Rushworth]], was unveiled in the state capitol by Governor [[Christine Gregoire]] on January 4, 2006.\n\nAfter leaving office, Locke joined the Seattle office of international law firm [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] [[LLP]], in their China and governmental-relations practice groups. During the leadup to the [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|2008 Democratic presidential primary]], Governor Locke signed on as Washington co-chairman of Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|bid for President]].<ref name=PI_Ammons_20071007>{{cite news |accessdate=October 17, 2007|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003932467_weblocke07m.html|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|title=Ex-governor Locke named Clinton state co-chair|last=Ammons|first=David|date=October 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of Commerce===\n[[File:GaryLockeFamily.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Locke's family awaiting the arrival of [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] in the [[White House]] on May 1, 2009]]\nOn December 4, 2008, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Locke was a potential candidate for [[U.S. Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] in then-President-elect [[Barack Obama]]'s cabinet. Eventually, then-[[Colorado]] Senator, [[Ken Salazar]], was nominated for that position instead.\n\nOn February 25, 2009, Locke was announced as President Barack Obama's choice for [[Secretary of Commerce]],<ref name=\"Sidoti\" /> and his nomination was confirmed by the United States Senate by unanimous consent on March 24, 2009.<ref name=confirmation>{{cite news|title=U.S. Senate Confirms Gary Locke as Commerce Secretary|publisher=[[United States Department of Commerce]]|date=March 24, 2009|url=https://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007824|accessdate=March 25, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327024230/http://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007824|archivedate=March 27, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Locke was sworn in March 26, 2009, by District Judge [[Richard A. Jones]],<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed|title=Locke Officially Leading Commerce|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2009|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2009/03/locke_officially_leading_comme.html|accessdate=March 29, 2009}}</ref> and he was sworn in by President Obama on May 1, 2009. Locke was the first Chinese American appointed as Secretary of Commerce, and one of three Asian Americans in Obama's cabinet, joining [[United States Secretary of Energy|Secretary of Energy]] [[Steven Chu]] and [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]] [[Eric Shinseki]]. ''[[Politico]]'' reported Locke had been a popular cabinet member among both businesses and the executive branch.<ref>{{cite news|title=CEOs: Locke Obama's Secret Weapon|publisher=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0211/48959.html}}</ref> A declaration of assets made in March 2011 showed Locke to be the sixth-richest official in the U.S. executive branch.<ref name=scmp20120518jiao>{{cite news|last=Jiao|first=Priscilla|title=Locke calls daily's bluff by declaring his assets|work=South China Morning Post|date=May 18, 2012|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/1001247/locke-calls-dailys-bluff-declaring-his-assets|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> {{clear}} [[File:Gary Locke official portrait for Department of Commerce by Michele Rushworth.jpg|thumb|Gary Locke's official portrait for the U.S. Department of Commerce was painted by [[Michele Rushworth]] ]]\n\n===Ambassador to China===\n[[File:Kurt Campbell with Chen Guangcheng at US Embassy May 1, 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Chen Guangcheng]] (left) with Locke (center) and [[Kurt M. Campbell]] (right) at the [[U.S. Embassy in Beijing]] on May 1, 2012]]\n\nFollowing the resignation of [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.]], Locke was nominated by President Obama to serve as [[United States Ambassador to China|U.S. ambassador to China]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama officially nominates Locke as China envoy |date=March 9, 2011 |url= http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politicsnorthwest/2014441720_obamaofficiallynameslockeambassdortochina.html |accessdate=March 9, 2011 |work=The Seattle Times |first=Kyung M. |last=Song}}</ref> The Senate confirmed Locke unanimously on July 27, 2011;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/galleries/pdcl/index.htm |title=U.S. Senate Periodical Press Gallery |publisher=Senate.gov |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126173242/https://www.senate.gov/galleries/pdcl/index.htm |archivedate=November 26, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Locke resigned as Secretary of Commerce on August 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/hillicon-valley/personnel-notes/174735-commerce-secretary-gary-locke-resigns-to-become-ambassador-to-china |first=Gautham |last=Nagesh |title=Commerce Secretary Gary Locke resigns to become Ambassador to China |work=The Hill |date=August 1, 2011 |accessdate=August 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA photo of Locke carrying his own knapsack and ordering his own coffee at the [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] went viral in China on the [[Sina Weibo]] [[social network]], with many commentators approving of his humble low-key style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/gary-locke-charms-china-by-carrying-own-bag/|title=Gary Locke charms China by carrying own bag|last=|first=|date=August 16, 2011|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=Associated Press|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.seattletimes.com/ABPub/zoom/html/2015927891.html|title=Gary Locke charms China by carrying own bag|last=|first=|date=|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/opinion/2011-08/19/content_13146941.htm |work=China Daily |title=Beijing welcomes you, Ambassador Locke |author=Patrick Mattimore |date=August 19, 2011  |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> At his first news conference after arrival in Beijing, Locke pledged to promote bilateral cooperation and understanding between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thechinatimes.com/online/2011/08/1035.html|title=New U.S. Ambassador Pledged to Promote Cooperation between U.S. and China |work=The China Times |accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEarly in Locke's ambassadorship, Chinese dissident [[Chen Guangcheng]] escaped from house arrest and sought refuge in the [[US Embassy in Beijing|U.S. Embassy in Beijing]] in April 2012. On May 2, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] demanded an apology from the U.S. for its role in the incident.<ref>[http://thinkingchinese.com/Chinas-Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-demands-that-the-US-apologizes-for-the-Chen-Guangcheng-incident \u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u8981\u6c42\u7f8e\u65b9\u5c31\u9648\u5149\u8bda\u4e00\u4e8b\u5411\u4e2d\u65b9\u9053\u6b49 \u2013 The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs demands that the US apologizes for the Chen Guangcheng incident] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CIJDqZvW?url=http://thinkingchinese.com/Chinas-Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-demands-that-the-US-apologizes-for-the-Chen-Guangcheng-incident |date=2012-11-19 }} (bilingual), [http://thinkingchinese.com Thinking Chinese], May 2012</ref> In an editorial on May 4, ''[[Beijing Daily]]'' questioned Locke's motives by taking in Chen<ref name=\"scmp20120518jiao\"/> and described Chen as \"a tool and a pawn for American politicians to blacken China.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/47289362#.T6Ne0utSSYk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505133854/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/47289362#.T6Ne0utSSYk |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 5, 2012 |title=China paper calls Chen a U.S. pawn; envoy is a \"troublemaker\" |author=Chris Buckley |date=May 4, 2012 |agency=Reuters |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn late November 2013, Locke announced that he would step down as ambassador to spend more time with his family in Seattle. In an analysis of his ambassadorship, Sun Zhe, a professor at [[Tsinghua University]] in [[Beijing]], said, \"It is not an easy job to be the American ambassador to China. Gary Locke is not a shining star, but a simple and unadorned ambassador.\" Shen Dingli, dean of the international studies department at [[Fudan University]] in [[Shanghai]], largely concurred, commenting that Locke \"showed us how a U.S. minister-level official behaves by taking economy-class flights\" but \"caused a twist\" when he allowed Chen refuge in the U.S. embassy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Denyer|first=Simon|title=U.S. Ambassador to China Gary Locke to step down, rejoin family in Seattle|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-ambassador-to-china-to-step-down-to-rejoin-family-in-seattle/2013/11/20/1b0ea914-51f1-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=November 20, 2013}}</ref> [[Max Baucus]], a former [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[Montana]], was President Obama's nominee to replace Locke and was confirmed by the Senate 96\u20130; Vice President [[Joe Biden]] administered the [[oath of office]] on February 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Herman|first=Malia Rulon|title=Max Baucus sworn in as ambassador|url=http://www.greatfallstribune.com/article/20140221/NEWS01/302210009/Max-Baucus-sworn-in-as-ambassador|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=[[Great Falls Tribune]]|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Ambassador===\nOn February 17, 2016, Locke joined the board of [[AMC Theatres]].<ref>{{cite press release | title = Gary Locke and John Zeng Join AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc. Board of Directors | publisher = [[AMC Theatres]] | date = 2016-02-17 | url = http://investor.amctheatres.com/file.aspx?IID=4171292&FID=32982956 | accessdate = 2016-08-08}}</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2016, Locke joined the board of the Seattle-based global health nonprofit [[PATH (global health organization)|PATH]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.path.org/news/press-room/766/|title=Announcement: PATH welcomes Governor Gary Locke to its board of directors \u2013 PATH|website=www.path.org|access-date=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n\nLocke has been a major proponent for Affirmative Action in Washington State. He publicly endorsed I-1000 in the 2019 Washington State general election. Those efforts were overturned by a majority of voters in the state of Washington in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Washington_Referendum_88,_Vote_on_I-1000_Affirmative_Action_Measure_(2019)#Support_for_an_approve_vote|title=Washington Initiative 1000, Affirmative Action and Diversity Commission Measure (2019)|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 he was featured in a 2020 Donald Trump reelection ad, portraying him with [[Joe Biden]] and mistakingly suggesting he was an official within the [[Chinese Communist Party]]. <ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/04/trumps-attacks-gary-locke/609844/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLocke's first marriage, to a law school classmate, ended with a divorce in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Simon |first=Jim |date=January 14, 1997 |title=Meet the governor of details |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970114&slug=2518777 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> On October 15, 1994, Locke married Mona Lee, a television reporter for the [[NBC]] affiliate [[KING-TV|KING 5 television]] in Seattle and former [[Miss Asian America]] 15 years his junior.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bjorhus |first=Jennifer |date=March 10, 1997 |title=First baby arrives: Emily Nicole Locke |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970310&slug=2528037 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> They divorced in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bayang |first=Ruth |date=May 12, 2017 |title=Lockes divorced, remain good friends |url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2017/05/lockes-divorced-remain-good-friends/ |work=Northwest Asian Weekly |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Meng |first=Angela |date=November 22, 2013 |title=Wife of US Ambassador to China Gary Locke denies he had affair |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1363267/wife-us-ambassador-china-gary-locke-denies-he-had-affair |work=South China Morning Post |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLee's parents immigrated to the United States from [[Taiwan]], and their ancestral roots in [[Mainland China]] include [[Shanghai]] (paternal) and [[Hubei]] (maternal). Mona Lee's father Larry has a half-sister [[Nora Sun]], daughter of [[Sun Fo]] and granddaughter of [[Sun Yat-sen]], father of modern China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.kitsapsun.com/archive/1997/10-11/0005_mona_lee_locke__state_s_first_lad.html|title=MONA LEE LOCKE: State's first lady connects with her Shanghai roots|publisher=[[Kitsap Sun]]|date=October 11, 1997|accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> The Lockes have three children: Emily Nicole (b. March 1997), Dylan James (b. March 1999), and Madeline Lee (b. November 2004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/bios/bio.htm |title=About Governor Gary Locke |publisher=Digitalarchives.wa.gov |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRegarding his ethnicity and being the only person of Chinese descent to have served as an ambassador to China, he said, \"I\u2019m proud of my Chinese heritage. I\u2019m proud of the great contributions that China has made to world civilization over thousands of years. But I\u2019m thoroughly American. I\u2019m proud of the great values that America has brought to the entire world and all that America stands for.\"<ref>Wan, William. \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-parting-speech-us-ambassador-urges-china-to-improve-human-rights-record/2014/02/27/5aabf59a-9f94-11e3-b8d8-94577ff66b28_story.html In parting speech, U.S. ambassador urges China to improve human rights record].\" ''[[The Washington Post]]''. February 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nWhen asked if there is place for Asian Americans in politics, Locke had this to say:\n\n\"I think our native cultures have emphasized respect for our elders, care of our elders, but also focusing on education. But my overall response is that Asian Americans are part and parcel of the great success of America. Our grandparents came over in the 1800s to work in the railroads, work the lumber camps, goldmines, worked in the canneries, farmland that most people thought could never raise a crop, worked as merchants in cities that were just emerging. They fought in world wars, died for our freedoms and our liberties. Asian Americans have given our blood, sweat and tears to the communities and to this country. There's a prosperity that we on the west coast enjoy. So much of the prosperity and progress of the western states is because of the blood, sweat and tears of Asian Americans. From doing the dirty work to fighting in our world wars and contributing to our society now as doctors, researchers, people in high tech, as innovators, in all different professions. We have every right, indeed a responsibility, to help set the policies that will move our communities and our nation forward.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kagy |first1=Tom |title=Gary Locke: Governor Fix-It |url=http://goldsea.com/Personalities/Lockegary/lockegary.html |website=Goldsea |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of the Chinese Americans in Seattle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gary Locke}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131017104242/http://beijing.usembassy-china.org.cn/ambassador11.html Ambassador Gary Locke]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100505192606/http://www.commerce.gov/OS/index.htm Biography] at the [[United States Department of Commerce]]\n*{{C-SPAN|garylocke}}\n* Gary Locke, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zujLO-LSULY \"Trends and Challenges of China's Economic and Technology Rise,\"] Keynote Address to China 2.0 Conference, Stanford Graduate School of Business, Oct. 24, 2013. <small>\u2014Video.</small>\n*{{NYTtopic|people/l/gary_locke}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-no99-30743}}\n*[http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/bios/bio.htm Bio of Gary Locke], [[Washington State Digital Archives]]\n*{{Charlie Rose view|12091}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King County Executive|Executive of King County]]|years=1994\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ron Sims]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Lowry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Washington]]|years=1997\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carlos Gutierrez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Commerce]]|years=2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Bryson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Lowry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Governor of Washington]]|years=[[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|1996]], [[2000 Washington gubernatorial election|2000]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Parris Glendening]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2002\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Vilsack]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dick Gephardt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Response to the State of the Union address]]|years=[[2003 State of the Union Address|2003]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Daschle]]<br />[[Nancy Pelosi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Huntsman, Jr.|Jon Huntsman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to China]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Max Baucus]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Obama cabinet}}\n{{USSecCommerce}}\n{{Governors of Washington}}\n{{US Ambassadors to the PRC}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Politics|Biography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locke, Gary}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to China]]\n[[Category:American people of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Taishan descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American state governors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American members of the Cabinet of the United States]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Franklin High School (Seattle) alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Obama administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Seattle]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Commerce]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Gary Locke}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{stack begin}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Gary Locke\n|native_name  = {{nobold|\u99f1\u5bb6\u8f1d}}\n|native_name_lang = zh-hant\n|image        = Gary Locke official portrait.jpg\n|office       = 10th [[United States Ambassador to China]]\n|president    = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = August 16, 2011\n|term_end     = March 1, 2014\n|predecessor  = [[Jon Huntsman Jr.]]\n|successor    = [[Max Baucus]]\n|office1      = 36th [[United States Secretary of Commerce]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Dennis Hightower]]<br />[[Rebecca Blank]] (acting)\n|term_start1  = March 26, 2009\n|term_end1    = August 1, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Carlos Gutierrez]]\n|successor1   = [[John Bryson]]\n|order2       = 21st [[List of governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]\n|lieutenant2  = [[Brad Owen]]\n|term_start2  = January 15, 1997\n|term_end2    = January 12, 2005\n|predecessor2 = [[Mike Lowry]]\n|successor2   = [[Christine Gregoire]]\n|office3      = 5th [[King County Executive]]\n|term_start3  = January 4, 1994\n|term_end3    = January 15, 1997\n|predecessor3 = [[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]]\n|successor3   = [[Ron Sims]]\n|state_house4 = Washington\n|district4    = 37th\n|term_start4  = January 10, 1983\n|term_end4    = January 3, 1994\n|predecessor4 = [[Peggy Maxie]]\n|successor4   = [[Vivian Caver]]\n|birth_name   = Gary Faye Locke\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1950|1|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Mona Lee|1994|2015|reason=div.}}\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Boston University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|showflag = j\n|t        = \u99f1\u5bb6\u8f1d\n|s        = \u9a86\u5bb6\u8f89\n|p        = Lu\u00f2 Ji\u0101hu\u012b\n|j        = Lok<sup>3</sup> Gaa<sup>1</sup> fai<sup>1</sup>\n|y        = Lok G\u0101f\u0101i\n}}\n{{stack end}}\n\n'''Gary Faye Locke''' (born January 21, 1950) is an American politician and diplomat who served as the 10th [[United States Ambassador to China|United States ambassador to China]] (2011\u201314). He was previously the [[List of Governors of Washington|21st Governor of Washington]] (1997\u20132005) and served in the [[Obama administration]] as [[United States Secretary of Commerce]] (2009\u201311).\nLocke is the first [[Governor (United States)|governor]] in the [[continental United States]] of [[Asian Americans|East Asian descent]], and is the only [[Chinese Americans|Chinese American]] ever to have served as a governor of any state. He was also the first Chinese American to serve as the U.S. ambassador to China.<ref name=\"TimeBio\">{{cite news|title=Commerce Secretary: Gary Locke|author=Gilbert Cruz|date=February 25, 2009|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1881587,00.html|accessdate=March 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGary Locke was born on January 21, 1950, in Seattle, [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and spent his early years living in the [[Yesler Terrace, Seattle|Yesler Terrace]] public [[public housing|housing project]]. A third-generation Chinese American with paternal ancestry from Jilong village,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2011/11/gary-locke-visits-his-family%E2%80%99s-ancestral-village-in-china-with-his-sister-rita/|title=Gary Locke visits his family's ancestral village in China with his sister Rita|date=12 November 2011|publisher=Northwest Asian Weekly}}</ref> [[Taishan, Guangdong|Taishan]], [[Guangdong]], [[China]], Locke is the second of five children of James Locke, who served as a [[Staff sergeant#United States|staff sergeant]] in the [[5th Armored Division (United States)|U.S. Fifth Armored Division]] during [[World War&nbsp;II]]. His wife, Julie, is from [[Hong Kong]],<ref>[http://www.thenewstribune.com/2011/01/16/1504584/jimmy-locke-father-of-former-gov.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111132348/http://www.thenewstribune.com/2011/01/16/1504584/jimmy-locke-father-of-former-gov.html |date=January 11, 2012 }}</ref> which at that time was a [[British Crown Colony]]/[[British Hong Kong]]. His paternal grandfather left China in the 1890s and moved to the United States, where he worked as a [[houseboy]] in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]], Washington, in exchange for [[English language|English]] lessons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Commerce Secretary Gary Locke on Asian-American and Pacific Islander Month 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z-f3mIn-HTI|date=April 30, 2010|publisher=Commerce News|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Gary Locke did not learn how to speak English until he was five years old and entered kindergarten.<ref name=\"english\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Remarks-by-President-Obama-and-Commerce-Secretary-Nominee-Gary-Locke/|title=Remarks by President Obama and Commerce Secretary Nominee Gary Locke|date=February 25, 2009|publisher=Whitehouse.gov|accessdate=July 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLocke graduated with honors from Seattle's [[Franklin High School (Seattle)|Franklin High School]] in 1968. He achieved [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] rank and received the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] from the [[Scouting in Washington (state)|Boy Scouts of America]].<ref name=\"english\"/><ref name=\"HistoryLinkBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?displaypage=output.cfm&file_id=7830| title=Locke, Gary Faye (b. 1950)|publisher=[[HistoryLink]]|author=Frank Chesley|date= June 29, 2006|accessdate=March 25, 2009}}</ref> Through a combination of part-time jobs, financial aid, and scholarships, Locke attended [[Yale University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] in 1972.<ref name=AsianBio>{{cite web|accessdate=November 9, 2008|url=http://www.asianamerican.net/bios/Locke-Gary.html|title=Biography of Governor Gary Locke|website=Who's Who of Asian Americans}}</ref> He later received his [[Juris Doctor|juris doctor]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1975.\n\n==Career==\n===Washington representative===\nIn 1982, Locke was elected to Washington state's South Seattle district in the [[Washington House of Representatives]], where he served as the chair of the Appropriations Committee. Eleven years later, in 1993, Locke was elected as [[King County, Washington|King County]]'s executive, defeating incumbent [[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]].\n\n===Governor===\n[[File:Gary Locke.jpg|thumb|left|Locke as Governor of Washington]]\nIn 1996, Locke won the [[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|Democratic primary and general election for governor of Washington]], becoming the first Chinese American governor in United States history. His political committee was fined $2,500 by regulators in 1997 after admitting to state campaign finance law violations during his successful campaign.<ref name=\"Sidoti\">{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090225/ap_on_go_pr_wh/obama_commerce |title=Obama selected Locke to run Commerce Department |agency=Associated Press |work=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Liz |last=Sidoti |date=February 25, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228162329/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090225/ap_on_go_pr_wh/obama_commerce |archivedate=February 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nLocke faced criticism from fellow Democrats for embracing the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]'s \"no-new-taxes\" approach to dealing with Washington's budget woes during and after the 2001 economic turmoil. Among his spending-reduction proposals were laying off thousands of state employees; reducing health coverage; freezing most state employees' pay; and cutting funding for nursing homes and programs for the [[developmentally disabled]]. In his final budget, Locke suspended two voter-passed school initiatives and cut state education funding. Supported by the state's political left, former [[Washington Supreme Court]] Justice [[Phil Talmadge]] announced his plans to challenge Locke in the 2004 Democratic primary, but Talmadge ended his campaign early for health reasons; Locke [[2000 Washington gubernatorial election|won re-election in 2000]].\n\nOn the national stage, Democrats saw Gary Locke as a possible vice-presidential choice. In 1997, Locke was a guest at that year's [[State of the Union address]].<ref>{{cite web|author = Clinton, Bill|title = Remarks By The President In State Of The Union Address|website = The White House|date = February 4, 1997|url = http://clinton2.nara.gov/WH/SOU97/|accessdate = February 24, 2009|quote = Gary Locke, the newly elected Governor of Washington State, is the first Chinese American governor in the history of our country. He's the proud son of two of the millions of Asian American immigrants who have strengthened America with their hard work, family values and good citizenship. He represents the future we can all achieve. Thank you, Governor, for being here. Please stand up.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716023357/http://clinton2.nara.gov/WH/SOU97/|archive-date = July 16, 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nLocke was chosen to give his party's response to [[George W. Bush]]'s [[2003 State of the Union Address]].<ref name=\"speaker\">{{cite press release|title = Democratic Leaders Announce Governor Gary Locke Will Deliver the Democratic Response to State of the Union Address|publisher = Congresswoman Nancy Pelosi|date = January 15, 2003|url = http://www.house.gov/pelosi/prGovGaryLocke011503.htm|accessdate = February 24, 2009|quote = Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle and House Democratic Leader Nancy Pelosi announced today that Governor Gary Locke of Washington state will deliver the Democratic response to President Bush\u2019s State of the Union address.|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090301105025/http://www.house.gov/pelosi/prGovGaryLocke011503.htm|archivedate = March 1, 2009|df = mdy-all}}</ref> In a surprise move, Locke announced in July 2003 that he would not seek a third term,<ref name=\"retire\">{{cite press release|title = Gov. Gary Locke Announces He Will Not Seek a Third Term|publisher = Washington State Office of the Governor|date = July 21, 2003|url = http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/press/press-view.asp?pressRelease=1403&newsType=1|accessdate =February 24, 2009|quote = }}</ref> saying, \"Despite my deep love of our state, I want to devote more time to my family.\"<ref name=\"retire\"/> [[Susan Paynter]], a columnist at the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'', suggested that racist slurs, insults, and threats that Locke and his family received, especially a large number which came after his rebuttal to George W. Bush's 2003 State of the Union address, may have played a role in Locke's decision to leave office after two terms.<ref name=PI_Paynter_20030726>{{cite news|url= http://www.seattlepi.com/paynter/132272_paynter25.html |accessdate=December 17, 2007|title= Threats to Locke's family are a factor in third-term decision|last= Paynter|first=Susan|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date= July 26, 2003}}</ref> The governor's office received hundreds of threatening letters and e-mails; others threatened to kill his children.<ref name=PI_Paynter_20030726/> His official portrait, painted by [[Michele Rushworth]], was unveiled in the state capitol by Governor [[Christine Gregoire]] on January 4, 2006.\n\nAfter leaving office, Locke joined the Seattle office of international law firm [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] [[LLP]], in their China and governmental-relations practice groups. During the leadup to the [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|2008 Democratic presidential primary]], Governor Locke signed on as Washington co-chairman of Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|bid for President]].<ref name=PI_Ammons_20071007>{{cite news |accessdate=October 17, 2007|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003932467_weblocke07m.html|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|title=Ex-governor Locke named Clinton state co-chair|last=Ammons|first=David|date=October 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of Commerce===\n[[File:GaryLockeFamily.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Locke's family awaiting the arrival of [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] in the [[White House]] on May 1, 2009]]\nOn December 4, 2008, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Locke was a potential candidate for [[U.S. Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] in then-President-elect [[Barack Obama]]'s cabinet. Eventually, then-[[Colorado]] Senator, [[Ken Salazar]], was nominated for that position instead.\n\nOn February 25, 2009, Locke was announced as President Barack Obama's choice for [[Secretary of Commerce]],<ref name=\"Sidoti\" /> and his nomination was confirmed by the United States Senate by unanimous consent on March 24, 2009.<ref name=confirmation>{{cite news|title=U.S. Senate Confirms Gary Locke as Commerce Secretary|publisher=[[United States Department of Commerce]]|date=March 24, 2009|url=https://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007824|accessdate=March 25, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327024230/http://www.commerce.gov/NewsRoom/PressReleases_FactSheets/PROD01_007824|archivedate=March 27, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Locke was sworn in March 26, 2009, by District Judge [[Richard A. Jones]],<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed|title=Locke Officially Leading Commerce|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2009|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2009/03/locke_officially_leading_comme.html|accessdate=March 29, 2009}}</ref> and he was sworn in by President Obama on May 1, 2009. Locke was the first Chinese American appointed as Secretary of Commerce, and one of three Asian Americans in Obama's cabinet, joining [[United States Secretary of Energy|Secretary of Energy]] [[Steven Chu]] and [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]] [[Eric Shinseki]]. ''[[Politico]]'' reported Locke had been a popular cabinet member among both businesses and the executive branch.<ref>{{cite news|title=CEOs: Locke Obama's Secret Weapon|publisher=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0211/48959.html}}</ref> A declaration of assets made in March 2011 showed Locke to be the sixth-richest official in the U.S. executive branch.<ref name=scmp20120518jiao>{{cite news|last=Jiao|first=Priscilla|title=Locke calls daily's bluff by declaring his assets|work=South China Morning Post|date=May 18, 2012|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/1001247/locke-calls-dailys-bluff-declaring-his-assets|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> {{clear}} [[File:Gary Locke official portrait for Department of Commerce by Michele Rushworth.jpg|thumb|Gary Locke's official portrait for the U.S. Department of Commerce was painted by [[Michele Rushworth]] ]]\n\n===Ambassador to China===\n[[File:Kurt Campbell with Chen Guangcheng at US Embassy May 1, 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Chen Guangcheng]] (left) with Locke (center) and [[Kurt M. Campbell]] (right) at the [[U.S. Embassy in Beijing]] on May 1, 2012]]\n\nFollowing the resignation of [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.]], Locke was nominated by President Obama to serve as [[United States Ambassador to China|U.S. ambassador to China]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama officially nominates Locke as China envoy |date=March 9, 2011 |url= http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politicsnorthwest/2014441720_obamaofficiallynameslockeambassdortochina.html |accessdate=March 9, 2011 |work=The Seattle Times |first=Kyung M. |last=Song}}</ref> The Senate confirmed Locke unanimously on July 27, 2011;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/galleries/pdcl/index.htm |title=U.S. Senate Periodical Press Gallery |publisher=Senate.gov |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126173242/https://www.senate.gov/galleries/pdcl/index.htm |archivedate=November 26, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Locke resigned as Secretary of Commerce on August 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/hillicon-valley/personnel-notes/174735-commerce-secretary-gary-locke-resigns-to-become-ambassador-to-china |first=Gautham |last=Nagesh |title=Commerce Secretary Gary Locke resigns to become Ambassador to China |work=The Hill |date=August 1, 2011 |accessdate=August 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA photo of Locke carrying his own knapsack and ordering his own coffee at the [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] went viral in China on the [[Sina Weibo]] [[social network]], with many commentators approving of his humble low-key style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/gary-locke-charms-china-by-carrying-own-bag/|title=Gary Locke charms China by carrying own bag|last=|first=|date=August 16, 2011|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=Associated Press|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.seattletimes.com/ABPub/zoom/html/2015927891.html|title=Gary Locke charms China by carrying own bag|last=|first=|date=|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/opinion/2011-08/19/content_13146941.htm |work=China Daily |title=Beijing welcomes you, Ambassador Locke |author=Patrick Mattimore |date=August 19, 2011  |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> At his first news conference after arrival in Beijing, Locke pledged to promote bilateral cooperation and understanding between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thechinatimes.com/online/2011/08/1035.html|title=New U.S. Ambassador Pledged to Promote Cooperation between U.S. and China |work=The China Times |accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEarly in Locke's ambassadorship, Chinese dissident [[Chen Guangcheng]] escaped from house arrest and sought refuge in the [[US Embassy in Beijing|U.S. Embassy in Beijing]] in April 2012. On May 2, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] demanded an apology from the U.S. for its role in the incident.<ref>[http://thinkingchinese.com/Chinas-Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-demands-that-the-US-apologizes-for-the-Chen-Guangcheng-incident \u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u8981\u6c42\u7f8e\u65b9\u5c31\u9648\u5149\u8bda\u4e00\u4e8b\u5411\u4e2d\u65b9\u9053\u6b49 \u2013 The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs demands that the US apologizes for the Chen Guangcheng incident] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CIJDqZvW?url=http://thinkingchinese.com/Chinas-Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-demands-that-the-US-apologizes-for-the-Chen-Guangcheng-incident |date=2012-11-19 }} (bilingual), [http://thinkingchinese.com Thinking Chinese], May 2012</ref> In an editorial on May 4, ''[[Beijing Daily]]'' questioned Locke's motives by taking in Chen<ref name=\"scmp20120518jiao\"/> and described Chen as \"a tool and a pawn for American politicians to blacken China.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/47289362#.T6Ne0utSSYk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505133854/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/47289362#.T6Ne0utSSYk |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 5, 2012 |title=China paper calls Chen a U.S. pawn; envoy is a \"troublemaker\" |author=Chris Buckley |date=May 4, 2012 |agency=Reuters |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn late November 2013, Locke announced that he would step down as ambassador to spend more time with his family in Seattle. In an analysis of his ambassadorship, Sun Zhe, a professor at [[Tsinghua University]] in [[Beijing]], said, \"It is not an easy job to be the American ambassador to China. Gary Locke is not a shining star, but a simple and unadorned ambassador.\" Shen Dingli, dean of the international studies department at [[Fudan University]] in [[Shanghai]], largely concurred, commenting that Locke \"showed us how a U.S. minister-level official behaves by taking economy-class flights\" but \"caused a twist\" when he allowed Chen refuge in the U.S. embassy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Denyer|first=Simon|title=U.S. Ambassador to China Gary Locke to step down, rejoin family in Seattle|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-ambassador-to-china-to-step-down-to-rejoin-family-in-seattle/2013/11/20/1b0ea914-51f1-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=November 20, 2013}}</ref> [[Max Baucus]], a former [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[Montana]], was President Obama's nominee to replace Locke and was confirmed by the Senate 96\u20130; Vice President [[Joe Biden]] administered the [[oath of office]] on February 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Herman|first=Malia Rulon|title=Max Baucus sworn in as ambassador|url=http://www.greatfallstribune.com/article/20140221/NEWS01/302210009/Max-Baucus-sworn-in-as-ambassador|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=[[Great Falls Tribune]]|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Ambassador===\nOn February 17, 2016, Locke joined the board of [[AMC Theatres]].<ref>{{cite press release | title = Gary Locke and John Zeng Join AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc. Board of Directors | publisher = [[AMC Theatres]] | date = 2016-02-17 | url = http://investor.amctheatres.com/file.aspx?IID=4171292&FID=32982956 | accessdate = 2016-08-08}}</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2016, Locke joined the board of the Seattle-based global health nonprofit [[PATH (global health organization)|PATH]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.path.org/news/press-room/766/|title=Announcement: PATH welcomes Governor Gary Locke to its board of directors \u2013 PATH|website=www.path.org|access-date=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n\nLocke has been a major proponent for Affirmative Action in Washington State. He publicly endorsed I-1000 in the 2019 Washington State general election. Those efforts were overturned by a majority of voters in the state of Washington in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Washington_Referendum_88,_Vote_on_I-1000_Affirmative_Action_Measure_(2019)#Support_for_an_approve_vote|title=Washington Initiative 1000, Affirmative Action and Diversity Commission Measure (2019)|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 he was featured in a 2020 Donald Trump reelection ad, portraying him with [[Joe Biden]] and mistakingly suggesting he was an official within the [[Chinese Communist Party]]. <ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/04/trumps-attacks-gary-locke/609844/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLocke's first marriage, to a law school classmate, ended with a divorce in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Simon |first=Jim |date=January 14, 1997 |title=Meet the governor of details |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970114&slug=2518777 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> On October 15, 1994, Locke married Mona Lee, a television reporter for the [[NBC]] affiliate [[KING-TV|KING 5 television]] in Seattle and former [[Miss Asian America]] 15 years his junior.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bjorhus |first=Jennifer |date=March 10, 1997 |title=First baby arrives: Emily Nicole Locke |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970310&slug=2528037 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> They divorced in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bayang |first=Ruth |date=May 12, 2017 |title=Lockes divorced, remain good friends |url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2017/05/lockes-divorced-remain-good-friends/ |work=Northwest Asian Weekly |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Meng |first=Angela |date=November 22, 2013 |title=Wife of US Ambassador to China Gary Locke denies he had affair |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1363267/wife-us-ambassador-china-gary-locke-denies-he-had-affair |work=South China Morning Post |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLee's parents immigrated to the United States from [[Taiwan]], and their ancestral roots in [[Mainland China]] include [[Shanghai]] (paternal) and [[Hubei]] (maternal). Mona Lee's father Larry has a half-sister [[Nora Sun]], daughter of [[Sun Fo]] and granddaughter of [[Sun Yat-sen]], father of modern China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.kitsapsun.com/archive/1997/10-11/0005_mona_lee_locke__state_s_first_lad.html|title=MONA LEE LOCKE: State's first lady connects with her Shanghai roots|publisher=[[Kitsap Sun]]|date=October 11, 1997|accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> The Lockes have three children: Emily Nicole (b. March 1997), Dylan James (b. March 1999), and Madeline Lee (b. November 2004).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/bios/bio.htm |title=About Governor Gary Locke |publisher=Digitalarchives.wa.gov |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRegarding his ethnicity and being the only person of Chinese descent to have served as an ambassador to China, he said, \"I\u2019m proud of my Chinese heritage. I\u2019m proud of the great contributions that China has made to world civilization over thousands of years. But I\u2019m thoroughly American. I\u2019m proud of the great values that America has brought to the entire world and all that America stands for.\"<ref>Wan, William. \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-parting-speech-us-ambassador-urges-china-to-improve-human-rights-record/2014/02/27/5aabf59a-9f94-11e3-b8d8-94577ff66b28_story.html In parting speech, U.S. ambassador urges China to improve human rights record].\" ''[[The Washington Post]]''. February 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nWhen asked if there is place for Asian Americans in politics, Locke had this to say:\n\n\"I think our native cultures have emphasized respect for our elders, care of our elders, but also focusing on education. But my overall response is that Asian Americans are part and parcel of the great success of America. Our grandparents came over in the 1800s to work in the railroads, work the lumber camps, goldmines, worked in the canneries, farmland that most people thought could never raise a crop, worked as merchants in cities that were just emerging. They fought in world wars, died for our freedoms and our liberties. Asian Americans have given our blood, sweat and tears to the communities and to this country. There's a prosperity that we on the west coast enjoy. So much of the prosperity and progress of the western states is because of the blood, sweat and tears of Asian Americans. From doing the dirty work to fighting in our world wars and contributing to our society now as doctors, researchers, people in high tech, as innovators, in all different professions. We have every right, indeed a responsibility, to help set the policies that will move our communities and our nation forward.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kagy |first1=Tom |title=Gary Locke: Governor Fix-It |url=http://goldsea.com/Personalities/Lockegary/lockegary.html |website=Goldsea |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of the Chinese Americans in Seattle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gary Locke}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131017104242/http://beijing.usembassy-china.org.cn/ambassador11.html Ambassador Gary Locke]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100505192606/http://www.commerce.gov/OS/index.htm Biography] at the [[United States Department of Commerce]]\n*{{C-SPAN|garylocke}}\n* Gary Locke, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zujLO-LSULY \"Trends and Challenges of China's Economic and Technology Rise,\"] Keynote Address to China 2.0 Conference, Stanford Graduate School of Business, Oct. 24, 2013. <small>\u2014Video.</small>\n*{{NYTtopic|people/l/gary_locke}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-no99-30743}}\n*[http://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/governorlocke/bios/bio.htm Bio of Gary Locke], [[Washington State Digital Archives]]\n*{{Charlie Rose view|12091}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Hill (politician)|Tim Hill]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King County Executive|Executive of King County]]|years=1994\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ron Sims]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Lowry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Washington]]|years=1997\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carlos Gutierrez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Commerce]]|years=2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Bryson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Lowry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Governor of Washington]]|years=[[1996 Washington gubernatorial election|1996]], [[2000 Washington gubernatorial election|2000]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Christine Gregoire]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Parris Glendening]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2002\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Vilsack]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dick Gephardt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Response to the State of the Union address]]|years=[[2003 State of the Union Address|2003]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Daschle]]<br />[[Nancy Pelosi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Huntsman, Jr.|Jon Huntsman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to China]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Max Baucus]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Obama cabinet}}\n{{USSecCommerce}}\n{{Governors of Washington}}\n{{US Ambassadors to the PRC}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Politics|Biography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locke, Gary}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to China]]\n[[Category:American people of Hong Kong descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Taishan descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American state governors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American members of the Cabinet of the United States]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Franklin High School (Seattle) alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Obama administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Seattle]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Commerce]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Wukai", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Locke"}
{"title_page": "Tom Felton", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor and singer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tom Felton\n| image              = TomFeltonNov2010.jpg\n| caption            = Tom Felton at the film premiere of [[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 1]]\n| birth_name         = Thomas Andrew Felton\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|9|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Epsom]], [[Surrey]], England\n| residence          = [[Venice Beach]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor| musician}}\n| years_active       = 1997\u2013present\n| known_for          = {{plainlist|\n*[[Draco Malfoy]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' franchise]]\n*[[Doctor Alchemy|Julian Albert]] in ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]''}}\n| website            = {{URL|tomfelton.com}}\n}} \n\n'''Thomas Andrew Felton'''<ref name=\"gofbio\">{{cite web |publisher=harrypotter.warnerbros.co.uk |title=Warner Bros. Official site |work=([[Adobe Flash|Flash]]: click appropriate actor's image, click \"Actor Bio\") |url=http://harrypotter.warnerbros.co.uk/gobletoffire/master/index.html |accessdate=5 August 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060410152155/http://harrypotter.warnerbros.co.uk/gobletoffire/master/index.html |archive-date=10 April 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (born 22 September 1987)<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tomfelton.com/news03.html |title=Wicked! Harry Potter's rival is not such a bad boy at home |accessdate=22 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070730191920/http://www.tomfelton.com/news03.html |archivedate=30 July 2007}}</ref> is an English actor and musician. He is best known for his role as [[Draco Malfoy]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|film adaptions]] of the best-selling ''[[Harry Potter]]'' fantasy novels by [[J.K. Rowling]]. His performances in [[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'']] and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' won him two consecutive [[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain|MTV Movie Awards for Best Villain]] in 2010 and 2011.\n\nPrior to ''Harry Potter'', Felton began appearing in commercials when he was eight years old for companies such as [[Commercial Union]] and [[Barclaycard]]. He made his screen debut in the role of [[The Borrowers|Peagreen Clock]] in [[The Borrowers (1997 film)|''The Borrowers'']] (1997) and he portrayed [[Louis T. Leonowens]] in ''[[Anna and the King]]'' (1999). Following the conclusion of the ''Harry Potter'' series in 2011, Felton appeared in the 2011 film ''[[Rise of the Planet of the Apes]]'', a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of the ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'' series.<ref name=\"BD\" /> He had roles in the minor films ''[[From the Rough]]'' (2011) and ''[[The Apparition]]'' (2012), and starred as [[Dido Elizabeth Belle|James Ashford]] in the critically acclaimed period drama film [[Belle (2013 film)|''Belle'']] (2013). He has since appeared in films such as ''[[In Secret]]'' (2014), ''[[Against the Sun]]'' (2014), ''[[Risen (2016 film)|Risen]]'' (2016), ''[[A United Kingdom]]'' (2016), and ''[[Feed (2017 film)|Feed]]'' (2017). He portrayed [[Doctor Alchemy|Julian Albert]] in ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFelton was born in [[Epsom]], the son of Sharon and [[Peter Felton]]. He was educated at [[West Horsley]]'s Cranmore School until the age of thirteen, after which time he attended The [[Howard of Effingham School]] as well as The Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. Felton is a singer and was part of a choir at the age of seven. He was a member of four school choirs and was offered a place in the [[Guildford Cathedral]] Choir. He has three older brothers: Ashley, Jonathan and Chris.<ref>[https://www.google.com/imgres?imgurl=http://www.twwn.net/Movie%2520Pictures/HP2dracodueling.jpg&imgrefurl=http://www.twwn.net/DidYouKnow/tom_felton.php&h=1500&w=2100&sz=389&tbnid=dZl2f_G0M1bABM:&tbnh=107&tbnw=150&prev=/search%3Fq%3Dguildford%2Bcathedral%26tbm%3Disch%26tbo%3Du&zoom=1&q=guildford+cathedral&usg=__nP9k_M1rRX-A1bY-UvPUMH7g50s=&hl=en-GB&sa=X&ei=8PTQT5_hMoXS0QWL0NDJCw&ved=0CD0Q9QEwDA/ The Wireless Wizarding Network-Profile of Tom Felton]. Retrieved on 7 June 2012</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nFelton began acting in adverts for companies such as [[Commercial Union]]<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/tv_film/newsid_3736000/3736247.stm Azkaban Exclusives: Draco Malfoy] from [[CBBC]]. Retrieved on 15 August 2007.</ref> and [[Barclaycard]].<ref name=\"official\"/> In 1998, he performed the voice of James in the television series ''[[Bugs (TV series)|Bugs]]'' and landed his first feature film role in 1997 when he played the role of Peagreen Clock in [[Peter Hewitt (film director)|Peter Hewitt's]] film ''[[The Borrowers (1997 film)|The Borrowers]]''.<ref name=\"mailonsunday\">[http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-147081/Prepare-Potter-magic.html Prepare for Potter magic!] from ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''. Retrieved on 15 August 2007.</ref><ref name=\"yahoo\">[https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800308596/bio Tom Felton biography] from [[Yahoo! Movies]]. Retrieved on 3 August 2007.</ref> Felton \nplayed witness Thomas Ingham opposite [[Clive Owen]] in ''[[Second Sight (TV series)|Second Sight]]'' in 1999.<ref name=\"mailonsunday\"/><ref name=\"flixster\">[http://www.flixster.com/actor/tom-felton Tom Felton biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080702121549/http://www.flixster.com/actor/tom-felton |date=2 July 2008 }} from [[Flixster]]. Retrieved on 3 August 2007.</ref> Felton's role of [[Louis T. Leonowens]] in the film ''[[Anna and the King]]'', starring [[Jodie Foster]], was also filmed in 1999 in [[Malaysia]].<ref name=\"official\"/> Felton made an appearance in the episode \"Hide and Seek\" of ''Second Sight 2'' followed in 2000.<ref>[http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-biography/tom-felton/ Tom Felton biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627011142/http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-biography/tom-felton/ |date=27 June 2008 }} from movies.msn.com. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref> The Guildford Cathedral Choir also offered him a position.<ref name=\"veritaserum\">[http://www.veritaserum.com/movies/actors/tomfelton.shtml Tom Felton biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110225810/http://www.veritaserum.com/movies/actors/tomfelton.shtml |date=10 November 2011 }} from [[Veritaserum]]. Retrieved on 3 August 2007.</ref>\n\n===2000\u2013present===\n\n[[File:Tom Felton Comic-Con cropped.jpg|thumb|Tom Felton at the Comic-Con Day 3 2010]]\nOn 11 November 2005, he and [[Rupert Grint]] presented Liz Carnell with the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''{{'}}s Pride of Britain Award for all of her work to raise awareness of the dangers of bullying.<ref>[http://www.hpana.com/news.18914.html Grint & Felton present award for anti-bullying Popular] from [[HPANA]]. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref><ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16233679&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=the-pride-of-britain-awards--special-award--liz-carnell--name_page.html The Pride of Britain Award: Special Award: LIZ CARNELL] from the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref> Felton worked on ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' throughout 2006.\n\nIn July 2007, Felton visited [[Children's Hospital (Aurora, Colorado)|Children's Hospital]] in [[Denver]], Colorado in a pre-screening, charitable event of ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix''.<ref>[http://www.hpana.com/news.20100.html 'Potter' actors attend charitable event in Denver Popular] from [[HPANA]]. Retrieved on 5 August 2007.</ref> He was also present at [[Leicester Square]] for the premiere of ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'' on 3 July 2007.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/2394887.stm Stars out for Potter premi\u00e8re] from [[BBC News]]. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/photoessay/0,4644,1998,00.html#8_0 European Premiere of 'Harry Potter'] from [[Fox News Channel]]. Retrieved on 5 August 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709124217/http://www.foxnews.com/photoessay/0,4644,1998,00.html#8_0 |date=9 July 2007 }}</ref>\n[[File:WW Chicago 2012 - Tom Felton 1 (7785837964).jpg|thumb|Felton in 2012]]\nOn 12 November 2008, Felton appeared alongside [[Jack Osbourne]] on ''[[Adrenaline Junkie]]'' as he participated in various challenges in South Africa, including a 200&nbsp;ft bungee jump on [[Bloukrans Bridge]], took a ride in a helicopter, followed by a parachute freefall and came face-to-face with [[great white shark]]s.\n\nWhen asked whether he was looking forward to playing a good guy in the future he answered: \"No. Well, I don't know. I suppose for now I'm happy with sticking to what he is. But after the Potter legacy is over I look forward to playing a good guy, or someone different anyway; someone not so spiteful.\"<ref name=\"scholastic\" /> Felton also played the character Simon in the 2009 horror/thriller movie ''[[The Disappeared (2009 film)|The Disappeared]]''.<ref>[http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/453942/The-Disappeared/overview The disappeared movie] from ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nFelton posted three music videos on YouTube under the account \"Feltbeats\", in which he performs fragments of original songs. Nine songs have been re-recorded and are now available on [[iTunes]]: \"Time Well Spent,\" \"Time Isn't Healing\", \"One of These Days\", \"Under Stars,\" \"Right Place, Right Time,\" \"In My Arms,\" \"All I Need,\" and \"I Will Be There\" join the instrumental \"Silhouettes in Sunsets.\" He also recorded an album titled ''In Good Hands''. It includes the six songs \"If You Could Be Anywhere\", \"We Belong\", \"When Angels Come\", \"Convinced\", \"Father of Mine\", and \"If That's Alright with You\".\n\nIn 2010, Felton released his original song \"Hawaii\" on Six String Productions<ref>[http://sixstringproductions.com/store.aspx] from ''SixString Website''.</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 an independent record label run by Felton, David Proffitt and Philip Haydn-Slater promoting creative independence and ownership of artists' material and musical talent.\n\nIn November 2010, the film ''White Other'', which Tom played the main character, Ray Marsden, was released. Tom's character Ray is a troubled youth in the \"ends\" of England and [[Imelda Staunton]], who played [[Dolores Umbridge]] in ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 1]]'', also makes an appearance as one of the other main roles in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whiteother.com/ |title=White Other official website |publisher=Whiteother.com |date= |accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nFelton had a cameo role in ''[[Get Him to the Greek]]'', released on 4 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snitchseeker.com/harry-potter-news/tom-felton-shoot-cameo-role-get-him-greek-66824/ |title=Tom Felton cameo with Jonah Hill |publisher=Snitchseeker.com |date=30 December 2010 |accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref> He portrayed the human character Dodge Landon in the 2011 [[science fiction|science-fiction]] film ''[[Rise of the Planet of the Apes]]'',<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/20933 |title='Harry Potter' Villain Helps Bring on the 'Rise of the Apes' |publisher= |date= |accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref> and played a paranormal investigator in the thriller film ''[[The Apparition]]'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35767/harry-potter-star-tom-felton-wave-his-wand-the-apparition |title=Harry Potter Star Tom Felton to Wave His Wand at The Apparition |publisher= |date= |accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2011, Felton appeared in a comedy sketch on [[Red Nose Day 2011]] alongside [[James Corden]], [[Rupert Grint]], [[George Michael]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[Ringo Starr]], former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|UK Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]], [[Robert Winston|Professor Robert Winston]] and [[Keira Knightley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://feltbeats.com/2011/03/18/video-tomfeltons-sketch-for-comic-relief-red-nose-day-and-trendic-topic/ |title=Video: Tom Felton's sketch for Comic Relief&nbsp;\u2013 Red Nose Day and Trendic Topic |publisher=Feltbeats.com |date=20 May 2008 |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 and 2017, Felton appeared as CSI [[Doctor Alchemy|Julian Albert / Doctor Alchemy]] on the third season of ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/06/30/the-flash-tom-felton-season-3-cast-julian-dorn-csi/|title=The Flash: Harry Potter's Tom Felton Joins Season 3 as Series Regular|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=30 June 2016|publisher=TVLine|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 2018, it was announced that Felton was cast in the series regular role of Logan Maine on the [[YouTube]] [[science fiction]] series ''[[Origin (TV series)|Origin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=\u2018Origin\u2019 YouTube Sci-Fi Series Sets Natalia Tena & Tom Felton As Leads, Paul W.S. Anderson As Director|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/origin-natalia-tena-tom-felton-star-youtube-red-sci-fi-series-1202377246/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=14 November 2018|date=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2003, Felton and his brother Chris worked with Joe Babbitt, the [[St. Lawrence County, New York|St. Lawrence County]] Angler's Association, the [[New York State Department of Environmental Conservation]] Region 6, the [[Chamber of Commerce]], and a diverse group of other organisations to form the World Junior Carp Tournament,<ref name=\"scholastic\">[http://teacher.scholastic.com/scholasticnews/indepth/harry_potter_movie/interviews/index.asp?article=tom_felton&topic=1 Tom Felton Talks About Reading, Collecting, and Being Draco] from [[Scholastic Corporation]]. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.hpana.com/news.19550.html Tom Felton in NY for Carp Tournament Popular] from [[HPANA]]. Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref> which involves competitive fishing for ages 11 to 18.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3718/is_200305/ai_n9279146 Lawrence lands World Junior Carp Tournament] from CNY Business Journal, archived at \"findarticles.com.\" Retrieved on 4 August 2007.</ref>\nFelton was in a relationship with his fellow co star from the Harry Potter series, Jade Olivia, from 2009 to 2016.<ref> \"Fans lose it as Harry Potter stars Tom Felton and Matthew Lewis reunite \"  nzherald https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12110025 </ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[The Borrowers (1997 film)|The Borrowers]]''\n|Peagreen Clock\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Anna and the King]]''\n|[[Louis T. Leonowens]]\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]''\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Draco Malfoy]]\n|Released as ''Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' in the US\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]''\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of 